window.NOVEL_CH = {
  1: {"n": 1, "title": "Chapter 1: The Man in the Cage", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A storm-dark 1993 InGen raptor transfer yard at night, floodlights cutting through rain, ex-military handlers around a steel transport crate, chain-link shadows across wet concrete, a dropped work glove near the cage track."}, "{{Jophery Brown}} had both hands on the gate when the crate moved.", "The rain had been falling for twenty minutes. It came down hard enough to turn the concrete apron outside the holding pen into black glass, hard enough that the floodlights made white rods out of the water. Men in rain ponchos stood around the transport crate with tasers and rifles and plastic face shields. The plastic shields were already fogged. The rifles were already wet.", "No one said the animal's name.", "They said <i>asset</i>. They said <i>female</i>. They said <i>the new one</i>. They said <i>keep the line tight</i>. They said <i>do not give her the corner</i>. The words were short, military, clipped. They moved from man to man as if a person could pass courage by radio.", "Jophery Brown was not new. Jophery Brown was thirty-one years old. He had grown up in Dorking, Surrey, in a house with a low garden wall, and he had come to Costa Rica through a contractor in Tampa whose office did not have the contractor's name on the door. He had sent his mother seventy pounds twice a month for two years. He had called his sister on Saturday afternoons her time, which was Saturday morning his time, and the phone in the staff hut had a coin slot for his colones. He was supposed to call her tomorrow. He had marked it on the cardboard backing of his shaving kit.", "Jophery Brown had worked four transfers and two feedings and one bad sedative recovery in the quarantine pens. He knew where to put his boots. He knew to keep his elbow out of the bite gap. He knew not to look into the dark inside the crate too long. The bad sedative recovery, last March, had been a dilo whose pulse went thin at thirty milligrams instead of forty. He had been the man who said <i>step back</i> before the doctor said it, and the doctor had remembered, and had said so to {{Robert Muldoon}}, who had said nothing, which was the way Robert Muldoon said yes.", "That night, the dark looked back.", "The transport crate struck the rail stop with a metal sound that cut through the storm. The rear gate dropped. The {{raptor}} hit the inner mesh before the handlers had finished shouting.", "The first strike bent the mesh.", "The second strike moved the crate.", "The third strike moved every man around it.", "\"Hold it!\" Robert Muldoon shouted.", "The handler on Jophery Brown's right slipped. His shoulder struck Jophery Brown's shoulder. Jophery Brown's left hand lost the wet bar for one second, not even a full second, just the amount of time it took a boot sole to slide on concrete.", "The raptor took that second.", "There was no roar at first. There was a shriek, high and close, like metal torn under pressure. The crate lurched back from the gate. Jophery Brown's arm went into the gap up to the shoulder, and then the rest of him followed the arm.", "Men grabbed his belt. Men grabbed his boots. Men shouted his name and then stopped using his name because names did not help.", "Jophery Brown saw the floodlight once, sideways. He saw rain on the rifle barrel above him. He saw Muldoon's face, pale behind the water on his cheeks.", "Then he saw the animal.", "Not the whole animal. Not a museum shape. Not a miracle.", "One yellow eye. One wet black claw hooked over the crate floor. The lower jaw opening sideways in the dark.", "Jophery Brown tried to pull his hand back.", "Something inside the crate pulled harder.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Low angle beside the transfer crate wheel on wet concrete, a torn ID lanyard and one dropped glove caught in floodwater, rain streaking through hard floodlights, the crate shadow looming over the apron."}, "\"Shoot her!\" Muldoon shouted.", "No one shot.", "For half a second no one shot because Jophery Brown was still between the guns and the animal. For the next half second no one shot because the handler with the rifle could not get his footing. Then the tasers snapped white into the rain, and the raptor screamed, and Jophery Brown's body struck the rail with a sound softer than the crate had made.", "The men pulled him out.", "They pulled him out by the belt and the back of his shirt and the right boot. One boot stayed on. The other came off and lay under the crate wheel with the laces untied. His badge lanyard had snapped. The badge itself was gone.", "Jophery Brown was still making a sound.", "It was not a word. It was a wet, surprised sound, as if part of his body had not been informed that the rest of him had ended.", "The InGen doctor ran in from the utility truck. The doctor was Hennig. The doctor had been in the truck because he had been told, when his contract was negotiated in Atlanta, that he would be present at all transfers and not within thirty meters of the cage. He had honored both terms. He honored neither tonight. The doctor knelt. The doctor put both hands on Jophery Brown's side and said, \"Pressure.\"", "No one had a clean towel.", "One of the handlers gave him a yellow rain poncho.", "The poncho turned dark in two breaths.", "Hennig pressed harder. Hennig knew where the femoral was, and he knew where the femoral was no longer. He pressed because pressing was what he had been taught to do, and because the men around him needed to see hands that had not stopped moving.", "Past the doctor, past the rain, past the men breathing hard behind their face shields, the raptor crate shook once more against the gate.", "Every man stepped back.", "Robert Muldoon did not.", "Muldoon lifted his rifle, but the raptor had already withdrawn into the darkness of the crate, and there was only a sound in there now. A low sound. A thinking sound.", "The men around the pen looked at the crate.", "The doctor looked at Jophery Brown.", "The InGen operations supervisor looked at the clipboard in his hand.", "The clipboard had a plastic cover. The paper inside was still dry.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "An InGen operations clipboard under a plastic rain cover, emergency incident boxes half-filled, the word RESTRICTED AREA stamped across the top, floodlights blurred behind it."}, "At 11:42 p.m., Jophery Brown was loaded into the helicopter.", "At 11:51 p.m., the holding pen was marked secure.", "At 12:04 a.m., the helicopter's pilot radioed in that he was carrying a Code Two passenger, which was the InGen radio code for a passenger who was not breathing. The duty officer at the medical building wrote <i>Code Two</i> on the night log and underneath wrote <i>receiving party not advised</i>, because the receiving party was a hospital in San José that had not been told what to expect, and would not be told.", "At 12:08 a.m., a man from Legal called the accident a restricted-area worker injury. The man from Legal was in a New York hotel room. He did not ask Jophery Brown's full name. He asked whether the worker had been a permanent or a contractor. He was told permanent. He said <i>that complicates this slightly</i>, in the way a man says it when nothing about the call has surprised him.", "At 12:19 a.m., someone from Operations asked whether the transfer yard could be cleaned before the investors arrived.", "No one answered at first.", "The rain did the answering. It pushed red water toward the service drain in slow threads. It carried straw, mud, torn cloth, and small pale curls of meat into the grate. From a distance, the curls did not look like meat. Up close, they were Jophery Brown.", "Beneath the grate, under the concrete, the drain sump clicked once as something hard struck the metal screen below.", "No one heard it.", "Everyone was looking at the cage.", "By morning, the first memo had gone out.", "The man who wrote it was a junior assistant in a borrowed office, and he had been given a list of phrases to choose from. The list had been made some time before, by someone who was no longer at InGen. The junior assistant did not know which phrase was the right one. He chose the one that sounded most like cleaning.", "It did not say death.", "It did not say eaten.", "It did not say that the workers had pulled Jophery Brown out of the mouth of an animal and then stood around him in the rain with nothing clean enough to press against the hole.", "It said <i>incident residue</i>.", "It said <i>biohazard closure</i>.", "It said <i>temporary sanitation support required immediately</i>."], "epigraph": {"text": "They said the pen was secure. They said it every time.", "attribution": "— InGen transfer log, Oct 1993"}},
  2: {"n": 2, "title": "Chapter 2: The Barback", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A Puntarenas waterfront bar at dawn in 1993, wet wooden floor, stacked plastic stools, a single bare bulb, the Pacific gray through louvered shutters."}, "It had been three weeks since the rent went late when Eduardo Brenes walked into La Sirena del Pacífico.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} was hosing the floor. The bar had closed at four. The cook had left with a paper sack of leftover yuca and a cigarette behind his ear. Mateo Valverde stood in rubber boots and pushed gray water toward the drain with a yellow plastic broom. The broom had lost half its bristles the month before. He had not replaced it because the owner did not see floors.", "He had been awake for twenty hours. The first eight he had been at his mother's apartment up the hill, fixing the loose pipe under her sink with a bicycle inner tube, because the plumber the building employed was on a <i>paseo</i> somewhere with the rent money the building had not yet been told about. The next eight he had been here, behind the bar, pouring beers for fishermen who tipped in change and leaving the change in the jar by the cash drawer because the owner counted the jar twice on Tuesdays. The last four he had been hosing the floor and thinking about the tube under the sink, which he was not certain would hold past Sunday.", "The shutters faced the Pacific. The Pacific was the color of an old radio.", "The door opened without a knock.", "Eduardo Brenes stood in the doorway with his hands in the pockets of a windbreaker that was newer than any windbreaker Eduardo Brenes had ever owned.", "\"<i>Maecillo</i>,\" Eduardo Brenes said.", "\"You are early,\" Mateo Valverde said. \"Or late. I cannot tell anymore.\"", "\"Early.\"", "Eduardo Brenes stepped inside. He did not sit. He looked at the stools stacked on the bar, at the framed photograph of the 1986 soccer team, at the calendar from a marine paint company nobody in Puntarenas had bought paint from in two years. He looked at the floor last. The floor was the only thing that was wet.", "\"You came back a month ago,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"You did not come here for a month.\"", "\"No.\"", "Mateo Valverde leaned the broom against the bar. Eduardo Brenes had been thinner the last time Mateo Valverde saw him. His shoes today were new. His teeth were not new. He had filled out around the jaw without filling out anywhere else, the way a man fills out when he has eaten food he did not work for.", "\"Coffee?\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"No.\"", "\"Beer?\"", "\"No.\"", "\"Are you here as a friend or as something else?\"", "Eduardo Brenes did not answer. He sat on a crate by the door instead, the way men sat when they had already decided a conversation would not last long enough to deserve a chair.", "\"I have a job for you,\" Eduardo Brenes said.", "\"What kind.\"", "\"Cleaning.\"", "\"Cleaning what.\"", "Eduardo Brenes looked at the floor.", "\"Cleaning a place,\" Eduardo Brenes said. \"Two weeks. Maybe less. The pay is in dollars.\"", "\"How many dollars.\"", "Eduardo Brenes told him the number.", "Mateo Valverde did not say anything for a moment. The number was the rent for four months, plus the medicine for his mother for two months, plus a pair of shoes if he wanted shoes, which he did not. He set his hand flat on the bar where the wood had gone smooth from elbows. He felt the edge of the laminate where it had begun to lift in the corner. He thought about the pipe under the sink up the hill, and about his mother's face when she had said <i>the inner tube will hold, the doctor never holds, you should worry about other things</i>, which had not been a permission and had not been a refusal.", "\"Where,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"You sign a paper before I can tell you where.\"", "\"That is not how a job works.\"", "\"That is how this job works.\"", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A Costa Rican man in his late twenties leans on a battered bar counter at dawn, a yellow plastic broom across the wood, a stranger in a new windbreaker visible in the doorway."}, "Eduardo Brenes took a folded envelope from the new windbreaker. Inside was a single page in English with a red-and-black skeleton inside a shield at the top. Mateo Valverde could not read English well, but he could read enough to see that the page asked him not to talk, and then asked him again, and then asked him in a third way that took up the bottom half of the paper.", "\"They sent you with this,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"They sent me to find one person.\"", "\"And you chose me.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Why.\"", "\"Because you are quiet. Because your mother does not ask questions about money.\"", "Mateo Valverde set the page on the bar. He pushed it once with his finger to flatten the fold.", "\"What happened to the last person,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Eduardo Brenes looked at the door, at the shutters, at the bare bulb above the bar. He did not look at Mateo Valverde.", "\"He went home,\" Eduardo Brenes said.", "\"Where is home for him.\"", "\"Not here.\"", "\"That is not an answer, Eduardo.\"", "\"It is the answer I have.\"", "Eduardo Brenes had been the boy who taught Mateo Valverde to clean fish. They had been ten and twelve, on the dock at the end of the road behind the cathedral, and Eduardo Brenes had shown him where the gill cover lifted and where the knife went in and where the spine ended on a <i>robalo</i>. Eduardo Brenes had been the man who lent him forty colones the week his father was buried, and had sat with him afterwards on a step at the back of the cemetery, not saying anything, which was the right thing to do that day. Eduardo Brenes had been the cousin to half the Puntarenas waterfront, and the friend to the half who were not cousins, and the one his mother always meant when she said <i>that boy</i> without naming a name.", "Eduardo Brenes was sitting on a crate now in a windbreaker that smelled of a store, and the way he was saying <i>he went home</i> was not the way a friend tells another friend that a man had gone home.", "\"You did this work,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"I did the grounds. Not what you would do.\"", "\"Was it bad.\"", "Eduardo Brenes did not answer.", "\"Eduardo.\"", "\"I bought a boat,\" Eduardo Brenes said. \"I did not buy a house with it, and I did not buy my mother a refrigerator with it. The boat is small and the boat is old. A boat is a thing you can leave in. Do you understand.\"", "Mateo Valverde understood and did not understand.", "He understood the part about the boat and the leaving. He did not understand why a man who had only done the grounds needed a boat to leave in.", "\"Sign the paper,\" Eduardo Brenes said. \"Or do not. Either way I do not come back here.\"", "Mateo Valverde signed the paper.", "He signed it with the pen behind the bar, the chewed-cap pen the cook used for the daily fish. The signature came out smaller than his usual signature. He noticed it. He did not redo it.", "Eduardo Brenes folded the paper back into the envelope, stood up from the crate, put a small slip with an address into Mateo Valverde's shirt pocket, and walked out without saying goodbye.", "The door swung once and stopped.", "Mateo Valverde finished hosing the floor.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A small concrete-floor room in a Puntarenas tenement, a cheap duffel bag half-packed on a single bed, a framed photograph of an older woman on the wall, gray morning light."}, "That night, Mateo Valverde packed.", "He packed the way a man packs when he does not know the weather. Two pairs of work pants. Three shirts. Rubber boots from the bar. A razor. A bar of soap. The small silver medal his mother had given him when he was eleven, of San Cristóbal, which she said was for travelers and which Mateo Valverde had only ever taken on the bus to Liberia and back. A paperback novel about a sailor he had not finished in two years. A man on a boat needed something to hold.", "He left the camera. The paper he could not read all of had said no photography.", "He sat on the edge of the bed and looked at the photograph of his mother on the wall. It had been taken in Liberia in 1979. She was wearing a yellow dress. Her hair was not yet gray. She was younger than Mateo Valverde was now, and standing next to a fence painted a color that did not exist in Puntarenas, and the man who had taken the photograph was Mateo Valverde's father, who had been alive that year, and had taken three more photographs of her in the same dress, which were in a tin box under the bed.", "He did not take the photograph down.", "He turned off the light.", "He did not sleep for a long time. The pipe under his mother's sink was eight blocks away. The inner tube was inside it. He thought about the inner tube. He thought about the forty colones from the week his father was buried, and how Eduardo Brenes had not asked for them back, and how that fact had become a thing between them that neither of them had ever spoken of, and was now not a thing he could speak of either, because Eduardo Brenes had said <i>I do not come back here</i>.", "In the morning, the slip in his shirt pocket said: <i>Hotel Rey de Oro, San José, sala de conferencias 4, 0900</i>.", "Mateo Valverde caught the 06:30 bus.", "He did not look back at the room.", "He did not need to. The room was inside him already, the way rooms got inside men who left them for the first time."], "epigraph": {"text": "The hourly number was not a hospital number.", "attribution": "— Mateo Valverde, nine days later"}},
  3: {"n": 3, "title": "Chapter 3: Restricted Questions", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A small San José hotel conference room in 1993, brown carpet, a folding table, a glass of water sweating on a paper coaster, a stack of carbon-copy forms beside a black telephone."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} had put on his best shirt.", "He had not decided to. He had taken the shirt out of the duffel bag and held it under the hotel bathroom's single bulb and looked at the collar for stains and, finding none, put it on instead of the work shirt he had packed first. The hotel off Paseo Colón was not a hotel Mateo Valverde would normally stand inside of. The lobby had polished tile and a man at the front desk in a jacket. Mateo Valverde had walked through it with the brown folder under his arm and the slip from his shirt pocket memorized, and the man at the desk had looked at him the way a hotel man looks at a person who is in the right place on a technicality.", "Sala de conferencias 4 was at the end of a beige hallway with a low ceiling and fluorescent tubes that buzzed at one frequency, then a lower one, then the first again. There was carpet the color of weak tea. There was a sign on the door that said PRIVADO. Mateo Valverde knocked.", "No one answered.", "He tried the handle.", "The room was already occupied.", "The fourth conference room at Hotel Rey de Oro had no windows. It had a folding table, three plastic chairs, a beige telephone, and a woman who did not look up when Mateo Valverde came in. The plastic name tag at her collar said CARMEN VEGA.", "\"Sit,\" Carmen Vega said.", "Mateo Valverde sat.", "Carmen Vega turned a stack of forms toward him slowly, the way a person turned a tray of fruit toward a buyer at the central market, and placed a white plastic pen on top of it. The pen had the red-and-black skeleton logo.", "\"Identification.\"", "Mateo Valverde gave her his <i>cédula</i>. She looked at it, at his face, at the <i>cédula</i> again. She wrote the number across the top of the first form without asking how to spell his name.", "\"You will sign three documents,\" Carmen Vega said. \"Initial four places in the second. Print your name in block letters in the third. The signatures must match. The pen does not leave the room.\"", "\"May I read them,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"You may. The rate of pay began at the first paper in Puntarenas. Careful reading takes forty minutes.\"", "\"I would like to read carefully.\"", "\"Then read.\"", "The first document was a confidentiality agreement. It said he would not discuss the nature, location, personnel, animals, or operations of the facility. The Spanish translation used the words <i>materia biológica</i>, which Mateo Valverde had only ever read on a sign at a hospital. Underneath the <i>materia biológica</i> clause was a sub-clause about information obtained indirectly. Under that was a sub-clause about information he might believe he had obtained, even if he had not. He read that one three times. He was not certain it said what he thought it said. He was not certain it did not.", "The second document was a medical disclosure. It asked for his blood type, his open wounds, his history with leptospirosis, rabies, or any zoonotic disease in the previous twelve months. <i>Zoonotic</i> was a word he had to ask about.", "\"Animal to person,\" Carmen Vega said. \"Or person to animal.\"", "\"What animals.\"", "\"The form does not require you to know.\"", "His blood type was O positive. He had known this since the year he worked the fish docks at Puntarenas, where the foreman required every man to write it in marker on the inside of the right wrist before the first shift. He had not been required to know it since, and the fact had gone ordinary in his mind, the way things go ordinary when they stop mattering. Now the box on the form made it matter again. He wrote it in the small square. His hand was steady. He had not expected it to be.", "No open wounds. No leptospirosis. No zoonotic disease in twelve months.", "He signed the second document and did not look at the word <i>zoonotic</i> again.", "The third document was a restricted-access waiver. It told him not to enter live zones, not to photograph the facility, and not to discuss the nature, circumstances, or personnel of prior sanitation incidents. He read the third line twice.", "\"Prior sanitation incidents,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"What does that mean.\"", "Carmen Vega did not look up.", "\"It means exactly what it says.\"", "\"Was someone hurt.\"", "Carmen Vega put her pen down. She placed both hands flat on the legal pad. She looked at Mateo Valverde for the first time.", "\"An incident has been logged,\" Carmen Vega said. \"The incident has been addressed. The facility is in compliance. The facility requires a temporary contractor in sanitation services. You are that contractor if you sign. If you do not sign, you receive travel reimbursement to Puntarenas and you do not return to this hotel.\"", "\"Has someone died.\"", "\"I cannot answer that.\"", "\"Cannot or will not.\"", "\"They are the same answer in this room.\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at Carmen Vega's face. She had the face of a woman who had given this answer before. Not once, not twice. She had the face of a woman who had given this answer enough times that it was no longer the answer to a specific question. It was simply what you said when you reached that point in the form.", "He thought of Eduardo Brenes sitting on the crate by the bar door.", "He thought of Eduardo saying: <i>A boat is a thing you can leave in.</i>", "He thought of the number on the payment voucher.", "\"The waiver,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "He read it one more time. Then he picked up the white plastic pen.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A logistics coordinator in a beige blouse stamps a carbon-copy form, a clipped name tag at her collar, a folded map of Costa Rica behind her, fluorescent ceiling light."}, "Mateo Valverde initialed four places: live zones, photography, prior incidents, and a line that said all biological waste encountered during the contract belonged to the company. He printed his name in block letters. He signed three times.", "Carmen Vega checked each signature against his <i>cédula</i> with a small plastic ruler. She did not say what she was checking for. She stamped each form with a black rubber stamp that said COMPLETO, the date, and a four-digit number that meant nothing to Mateo Valverde. She put the forms into a manila folder, and the folder into a metal box on the floor beside her chair. The metal box had a padlock.", "He watched the padlock close.", "The thought was small. Not large enough to say aloud, not large enough to act on. The size of a thought a man has in a windowless room with a buzzing light when he is tired and has just signed his name three times to papers he cannot keep. <i>Those are mine.</i> His name, his blood type, his clean wrists, his mother's injections at forty-two hundred colones each. Now in a box in a beige hotel room in San José, in the keeping of a woman he had met thirty minutes ago, who would carry that box somewhere Mateo Valverde would never see.", "Carmen Vega did not look at him having this thought.", "\"You will receive a copy of the confidentiality agreement,\" Carmen Vega said. \"You will not receive a copy of the medical disclosure. You will not receive a copy of the waiver.\"", "\"Why not.\"", "\"Because you have agreed not to retain documents from the facility.\"", "\"This is not the facility.\"", "\"The forms are facility documents. They are restricted.\"", "She slid a single carbon-copy page across the table. The signature at the bottom was a faint blue. She put the page into a plain brown folder and gave him the folder.", "\"You will not open this in public,\" Carmen Vega said.", "\"It is mine.\"", "\"It is yours. You will not open it in public.\"", "She slid one more page across the table.", "\"Travel voucher. Bus to Puntarenas. Tonight. Boat at zero five hundred from dock seven. Bring identification. Bring this folder. Do not bring anything you cannot lose.\"", "The voucher was for a single passenger. It had no return.", "Mateo Valverde folded the voucher into the brown folder. He stood. Carmen Vega had already turned back to her legal pad. She wrote something with a different pen, a regular blue pen from a box, the cheap kind, and she wrote without looking at what she wrote, as if her hand had memorized the line, as if the line were not about anyone in particular anymore, as if this room had been full of men in their best shirts and all of them had left the same way.", "\"Thank you,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Carmen Vega wrote.", "Mateo Valverde left.", "The hallway was still beige. The fluorescent tubes still buzzed. At the far end, a housekeeper pushed a cart with one wheel that caught on the carpet. The cart made a small sound each time the wheel caught. Mateo Valverde walked past it, out through the lobby, and into the afternoon of Paseo Colón.", "He stood on the sidewalk for a moment.", "He did not open the folder.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A 1993 Costa Rican cross-country bus at dusk, a tired man in a clean shirt by a window holding a brown manila folder closed with both hands, San José city lights smearing past."}, "At 16:08, Mateo Valverde left Hotel Rey de Oro.", "At 17:30, he boarded the bus to Puntarenas.", "The bus was full. It smelled of plastic seat covers and someone else's coffee. He sat by the window with the brown folder on his knees. The folder weighed exactly one carbon-copy page, but he held it the way a man holds a thing he has been told not to drop.", "He thought of Carmen Vega's hands flat on the legal pad. He thought of the metal box with the padlock. He thought of a stamp number that meant something to someone who was not on this bus.", "He did not let himself add the money up in the conference room. He added it up now, as the bus moved through Escazú. Fourteen days times the hourly rate. He divided the total by the rent. Four months and twelve days, nothing left over, not for the medicine, not for shoes. Then he did it again with the overtime rate listed in small print on the second page. Four months and twelve days became five months.", "His mother did not take expensive medicine. The injections were forty-two hundred colones each. The doctor had said twice a month, which the doctor knew they could not afford, so they had agreed on once a month, which the doctor had not written down.", "At the window, San José became smaller.", "At the window, the Pacific appeared, first in pieces between hills, then in a long gray line below the highway.", "He thought about Eduardo Brenes saying <i>a boat is a thing you can leave in</i>. He thought about Eduardo's shoes, new shoes, and about Eduardo's boat, which Eduardo had described as old and small. Eduardo Brenes had been the boy who taught Mateo Valverde to clean fish. He had also always known how to find the place where a knife should go. He had come to La Sirena at four in the morning, before any sensible man's day started, as if he had timed the conversation to happen in a place where Mateo Valverde would have nowhere to walk away to.", "The man in the seat beside Mateo Valverde fell asleep against the window before Escazú was behind them. He had a briefcase on his lap and a loosened tie and the settled look of a man who took this bus often enough to sleep through the curves.", "Mateo Valverde watched him sleep.", "He did not sleep.", "He arrived in Puntarenas at 21:47.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-4.webp", "alt": "The Puntarenas esplanade at near-midnight in 1993, a long concrete seawall, a single lit fisherman's kiosk, black water beyond the low wall, the Gulf of Nicoya invisible in the dark."}, "The bus depot was three blocks from the esplanade. Mateo Valverde walked the three blocks with the duffel over one shoulder and the brown folder under the same arm and the night air off the gulf against his face. Puntarenas at midnight was quiet. The waterfront kiosks were shuttered except for one, where a man sold refresco from a bucket of ice to a young couple who had no interest in the refresco.", "Dock seven was visible from the esplanade. There was a light over the gate. The gate was locked.", "Mateo Valverde found a bench on the esplanade and sat with the duffel between his feet.", "It had been the bar. It had been Eduardo Brenes in his new windbreaker at four in the morning. It had been Carmen Vega with her padlock and her legal pad and her face that had given the same answer so many times it had stopped being about anyone. He was here now.", "The gulf was black. Somewhere out there, invisible, was an island where something had put a man in a helicopter at 11:42 at night, and another man behind a desk at Hotel Rey de Oro the next morning, and Mateo Valverde on a concrete bench with seven hours left to wait.", "He thought about calling his mother. There was a phone kiosk at the bus depot. He had coins enough.", "He did not call.", "There was nothing to say that would not require explaining the folder. He could not explain the folder. His mother would hear the thing he was not saying, the way she always heard it, and ask in the particular way she asked, which was not a question but a long silence on her end of the line, and Mateo Valverde was not ready for that silence.", "He sat.", "At some point a fishing boat came in past the dock lights, running dark except for the red and green at its bow. He watched it.", "The boat was at 05:00."], "epigraph": {"text": "You lose that, you don't exist.", "attribution": "— Dale Haskins, contractor orientation"}},
  4: {"n": 4, "title": "Chapter 4: The Crossing", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Puntarenas dock seven before dawn in 1993, a steel supply boat with a red-and-black logo on the hull, wet bollards, a thermos beside a coil of rope, gray water."}, "The boat was called the <i>Anne B. II</i>. The name was painted on the stern in red letters touched up unevenly, the second N newer than the first. The hull was steel. The wheelhouse had a red-and-black skeleton inside a shield stenciled on the door.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} stood on the dock with his duffel and the brown folder. The night had thinned but the dawn had not arrived. The water in the slip was the color of black tea and moved against the pilings without making any sound at all. There was a thermos on a bollard beside the gangway, and a coil of nylon rope, and one orange life ring that had been cleaned recently enough that the salt had not had time to come back into it. The rope was not coiled the way a fisherman coiled rope. It was coiled the way a man coiled rope when he had been told what shape the coil should be.", "A man in a wet jacket checked Mateo Valverde's <i>cédula</i> at the gangway. He checked the brown folder without opening it, holding it in two hands the way a baker holds bread, then gave it back.", "\"Below,\" the man in the wet jacket said.", "Below was a low cabin with four bench seats and a folding table and a coffee urn that did not look as if it had ever been emptied. Four other workers were already there.", "Two of them wore badges on lanyards. The badges were laminated and worn at the corners. The lanyards were faded. One of the men had a piece of green tape on the back of his lanyard clip, of the kind a person used to mark his own things when he kept his things near other men's. These two did not look up.", "The third was a man in a tan canvas jacket and a baseball cap with a fishing-supply company logo. He was American. He looked up as soon as Mateo Valverde came down the steps.", "\"Cliff Donegan,\" the American said. \"Maintenance. Texas. You?\"", "\"Mateo Valverde. <i>Saneamiento</i>.\"", "\"Sanitation. Got it. First time?\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Me too. Well, second. Did a week last year for these people. Different island. Coffee?\"", "\"Thank you, no.\"", "\"Suit yourself. Coffee on the island is worse anyway.\"", "Cliff Donegan smiled at the joke he had just made. The smile was the smile of a man who told the same jokes in three countries and had stopped counting which ones landed. He had the kind of forearms that had been heavy lifting since high school. He had a wedding ring. He had a small white scar on the second knuckle of his right hand.", "The fourth worker was a woman. She sat at the far end of the bench with a small duffel bag between her feet. Her hair was pulled back tight under a kerchief and her hands were red at the knuckles in the way that the hands of people who washed dishes for a living were red at the knuckles.", "\"Paola Ruiz,\" she said quietly, when Mateo Valverde looked her way.", "\"Mateo Valverde.\"", "\"Cocina del personal.\"", "\"Sanitation.\"", "She looked at him a second longer than he expected. Then she looked at her duffel bag.", "The boat began to move.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "The interior cabin of a 1993 supply boat at dawn, four workers on bench seats with badges and duffel bags, a coffee urn under a yellow bulb, a porthole showing rain on gray water."}, "The rain started at the second hour. By the third the sea had what the captain called a <i>pequeño chop</i>, which Mateo Valverde understood to mean a chop that was not small. Cliff Donegan was sick into a metal bucket for forty minutes. The two badged workers did not get sick. They sat with their elbows on their knees and their hands folded, and they did not speak to each other except to ask for the salt.", "Paola Ruiz did not get sick either. She sat with her duffel between her feet, her back against the bulkhead, her eyes on the porthole. She had a way of being still that did not look like fear. It looked like a habit. The way a woman who had spent a lot of years standing at a stove did not waste effort on the small movements of waiting.", "Mateo Valverde tried, in the way a careful man tries.", "\"You have done this trip before,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes,\" the older of the two said.", "\"You are returning.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"How many weeks.\"", "\"Two.\"", "\"And the work is what.\"", "The older man looked at his hands.", "\"The work is what they tell you the work is,\" the older man said.", "The younger of the two was a thin man with a deep crease between his eyebrows that had been put there by squinting in sun. He had not said anything since Mateo Valverde came aboard. He looked up now.", "\"You are the new one,\" the thin man said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Sanitation.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "The thin man looked at the older man. The older man did not look back. The thin man looked at the porthole.", "\"Jophery was good,\" the thin man said.", "The cabin was quiet enough after that to hear the bucket slide six inches when the boat heeled.", "\"Jophery,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Was good,\" the thin man said again.", "The words were not a name. They were a closed door.", "Mateo Valverde waited. He waited the way he waited at the bar when a customer was deciding whether to order another beer or to leave. He waited a full minute. The thin man did not say anything else. The older man did not say anything else. Cliff Donegan made a noise into the bucket that was not a word.", "Paola Ruiz, at the far end of the bench, watched all of this without moving her head.", "\"Was he the man before me,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "The older man stood up. He did not answer. He went up the cabin steps and stood under the lip of the wheelhouse roof where the rain could not reach him, and he stayed there until the island came into view.", "The thin man stayed in the cabin and looked at the porthole.", "Mateo Valverde stayed where he was. He thought about Carmen Vega's hand flat on the legal pad. He thought about Eduardo Brenes saying <i>he went home</i>. He thought about the fact that nobody on this boat had said <i>he is dead</i>, even though everybody on this boat knew. The not-saying was a thing the men did with their hands and their shoulders, a thing they passed without speaking, a courtesy among men who had agreed to a price for their courtesies.", "He had taken the same price.", "He looked at his own hands.", "His hands were cold.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A misty silhouette of Isla Nublar's volcanic ridge through rain at midday, a steel supply boat low in the swell, yellow emergency lights along a concrete service dock ahead."}, "The island came up out of the rain in pieces. First the ridge, which was the color of an old roof. Then the trees, which were the color of trees. Then the cliffs, which were the wrong color, because the cliffs had a band of gray concrete along the bottom that no cliff in nature had ever had. The concrete was a sea wall. The sea wall ran for what looked to Mateo Valverde like half a kilometer. The sea wall had a service dock cut into the middle of it, and yellow emergency lights along the edge of the dock, and a single steel gantry crane that was not moving.", "There were no guests visible.", "There was no welcome sign.", "There was a sign that said SERVICE in English and <i>SERVICIO</i> in Spanish, and beside the sign there was a smaller sign that said NO UNAUTHORIZED ENTRY, in English only.", "The <i>Anne B. II</i> slid against the dock with a soft heavy thud.", "Three men in green rain jackets came out of a small concrete building. They wore the same red-and-black skeleton patch on their sleeves. Two of them were holding rifles. The third was holding a clipboard.", "The man with the clipboard checked names in the order they were on the list, not the order the workers came off the boat. He did not say good morning.", "\"Donegan.\"", "\"Yo.\"", "\"Valverde.\"", "\"Sí.\"", "He wrote a small mark next to each name. The two badged workers did not need their names called. They walked past him and went through a door in the concrete building without looking back.", "Mateo Valverde watched the door close behind them.", "The rain on the dock was warmer than the rain on the boat had been. It came down in a way that did not feel like rain coming down. It felt like rain coming up from the ground. The yellow lights on the edge of the dock gave the wet concrete a color that was not a color of weather, but a color of a place where something had been hosed off recently.", "He looked at the seam where the dock met the concrete building. The seam was clean. Somewhere along its length, in the last day or two, somebody had run a pressure hose along that seam, because the line of dirt that should have been there was not there, and the line of pale concrete that took its place had not been bleached evenly.", "\"Follow,\" the man with the clipboard said.", "They followed.", "Behind them, the <i>Anne B. II</i> was already being loaded with crates Mateo Valverde had not seen come up from below. The crates were taped, labeled, and quiet. The crane began to move. The boat would leave at 16:30.", "The boat would not be back for fourteen days.", "Mateo Valverde walked between Cliff Donegan, who was wiping his mouth on the back of his hand, and Paola Ruiz, who was carrying her duffel against her chest the way a woman carried something she did not want a stranger to brush.", "He did not look at the gantry crane.", "He did not look at the door the badged men had gone through.", "He looked at his boots, which were already darker than they had been on the boat, and at the wet concrete under them, and at the seam he had decided not to think about.", "The man with the clipboard pulled open the door of the concrete building.", "Mateo Valverde walked through."], "epigraph": {"text": "The confidentiality rules are not complicated. You don't talk about what you don't see.", "attribution": "— InGen NDA, Section 4, subsection (c)"}},
  5: {"n": 5, "title": "Chapter 5: The Canteen", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A 1993 InGen prefab barracks dining area near the service dock, a long folding table under a single fluorescent strip, gray rain on louvered windows, plastic trays stacked."}, "The prefab building sat on concrete blocks at the inland edge of the service dock. It was the color of a thing bought from a catalog. The roof was corrugated metal. The walls were corrugated metal painted the color of a building nobody wanted to look at. The door was a screen door inside a steel door, and both doors closed with springs that did not match.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} reached the building behind Cliff Donegan and Paola Ruiz. The path from the dock was concrete with a weed line down the middle that had been kept down by foot traffic but not by chemicals. The rain had eased into a drift. Off to one side, behind a chain-link gate the man with the clipboard had not pointed out, a row of green coveralls hung on a wire to drip dry. The coveralls had been washed in cold water. The water had not gotten the orange line out of the cuff of the third one along.", "Inside there were two rooms. The first had bunks. The second had a folding table longer than the room was wide, plastic chairs on both sides, a coffee urn, a stack of metal trays, and a single fluorescent strip across the ceiling.", "The strip flickered. Not steadily. It flickered at the rhythm of a man who could not remember the next word.", "Mateo Valverde took a tray.", "The food on the tray was rice, black beans, a piece of fried plantain, a piece of chicken cooked twice, and a small plastic cup of bright yellow gelatin with a piece of canned pineapple suspended in it. The food was the food of a place that had been told to feed Costa Rican workers and had asked someone in an office in California what Costa Rican workers ate. The chicken had been fried in the morning and kept warm under a heat lamp until the workers walked in, which had happened just after eleven hundred. The lamp had also kept the gelatin warm. The pineapple in the gelatin was warmer than the gelatin around it.", "He sat down across from Paola Ruiz.", "\"You may sit somewhere else,\" Paola Ruiz said.", "\"I would rather not.\"", "\"Then sit.\"", "She had already eaten half her rice. She ate quickly, not the way a hungry person ate, but the way a person ate when she had been told that someone else needed the table.", "\"How long have you been on the island,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Since the boat with you.\"", "\"That was four hours ago.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"It feels longer.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "The two badged workers from the boat were at the far end of the table. They were eating faster than Paola Ruiz. They did not speak. They did not look at each other. They held their forks the way men held tools they had used for too long, and they finished their plates before Mateo Valverde had taken three bites.", "The thin one stood up first. He carried his tray to the bin, scraped it, set the tray on the rack.", "Then he turned.", "He walked back the long way past the table, on Mateo Valverde's side, and as he passed he looked down at the green badge clipped to the front of Mateo Valverde's coveralls. He did not stop walking. He did not slow. He did not say anything. He looked at the badge for the time it took him to take three steps past the chair, and that was longer than a man looked at a thing he was not interested in.", "The screen door opened. The screen door closed.", "The older worker followed him out a few seconds later. The older worker did not look at the badge. The older worker did not look at Mateo Valverde at all. He walked the way men walked when they had agreed earlier in the day not to look at certain things, and were keeping that agreement in front of a stranger because the agreement was older than the stranger.", "The two of them were gone.", "The fluorescent light flickered.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Two workers eating from metal trays at a long folding table, one in a green temporary badge, the other a tired food-service woman, a flickering ceiling light overhead, rain on the windows behind them."}, "\"Paola,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Why does he look at my badge like that.\"", "Paola Ruiz did not look up. She moved her fork through the rice in a small careful pattern. She moved a piece of plantain to one side of the tray. She moved it back.", "\"Paola.\"", "\"I do not know him.\"", "\"He is from this island. You are from this island now. What does the look mean.\"", "\"I do not know him,\" Paola Ruiz said again.", "\"You heard something.\"", "She looked up.", "She looked at him the way a person looked at someone they were about to like or dislike for a long time, and they had not decided yet. Her eyes had small wet dark things in them, of the kind that appear in the eyes of people who have been told to be quiet many times in a row and were tired of the quiet.", "\"I heard at the dock,\" Paola Ruiz said, \"while you were giving your <i>cédula</i>, that the badge is a sanitation slot.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"That is what I heard.\"", "\"And.\"", "\"And nothing.\"", "\"Paola.\"", "\"And nothing, Mateo Valverde. The man with the clipboard said sanitation slot, and one of the men with rifles said <i>the sanitation slot</i>, and the man with the rifle did not say anything else.\"", "\"He said <i>the</i> slot.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Not <i>a</i> slot.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "She started eating faster. She ate the rest of the rice in three forkfuls. She ate the chicken without cutting it. She drank the gelatin in one swallow. She stood up with her tray.", "\"I am sorry,\" Paola Ruiz said.", "\"For what.\"", "\"For sitting at this table for shorter than I would have.\"", "She carried her tray to the bin. She scraped the tray. She set the tray on the rack. She walked out of the dining room into the bunk room without looking back. The door between the two rooms closed with a soft swing of a spring that did not match its other spring.", "Mateo Valverde sat alone at the long folding table.", "The fluorescent light flickered.", "He ate the rest of his food slowly, because he did not want to stand up, and because he did not want to be the next person to walk out of the dining room and let the spring on the door make a sound that the room would remember.", "He thought about the article <i>the</i>. He thought about the article <i>a</i>. He thought about how a country with very precise rules for both articles had been content to give him a badge that said TEMPORARY CONTRACTOR and not TEMPORARY CONTRACTOR REPLACEMENT, and how the difference between the two phrases lived in the article a man with a rifle had used at a dock in a rain that came up from the ground.", "The rain had gotten back into the chicken at the tray's edge. He left the chicken.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A single Costa Rican worker sits alone at a long folding table under one fluorescent light, his green temporary badge bright against off-white coveralls, rain streaks on the louvered window behind him."}, "When he finished he carried his tray to the bin, scraped it, set it on the rack.", "He looked at his badge.", "The badge said his name. The badge said TEMPORARY CONTRACTOR. The badge said SANITATION / BIOHAZARD. The badge said VALID: FOURTEEN DAYS.", "The badge did not say <i>the slot</i>.", "He turned off the dining room light by habit. The fluorescent strip went dark. A second strip he had not noticed, in the corner above the bins, came on by itself, in a way that meant the building had decided when a room was occupied and when a room was not.", "He stood very still.", "The corner light flickered too.", "He went into the bunk room and lay down on the bunk farthest from the door. The bunk had been used recently. The pillow had a slight depression in the center the way a pillow had a depression in the center after the head of a person who had not slept well. The blanket had been folded square at the foot of the bed by a person who had been trained to fold blankets square. Mateo Valverde understood without thinking about it that the blanket had been folded by an InGen handler who had cleaned the bunk after the last man, and not by the last man. Men who had been told they were leaving did not fold their blankets square.", "There were three other bunks in the room. Two had men in them already. He did not know when those men had gotten in. They had not been at dinner. The thin one was on the bunk by the window and his face was turned to the wall. The older one was on the bunk against the far wall and his face was also turned to the wall. They were both still in their clothes. They had taken off their boots and not their socks. They were not asleep, because their breathing was not the breathing of sleeping men, but they had decided the way men decided in barracks that they would not be the man who said the next thing.", "Paola Ruiz was not in this room. Her duffel was beside the door of a smaller room that had no sign on it. The door was closed.", "Sleep did not come for a long time.", "When it came, he heard the screen door close, and the steel door close behind it, in the order they had closed when the two men had left, and then he heard them close again, and he understood without understanding that the building had been built by people who wanted everything to close twice."], "epigraph": {"text": "The island looked wrong from the water.", "attribution": "— Cliff Donegan, maintenance, Texas"}},
  6: {"n": 6, "title": "Chapter 6: Two Briefings", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A bare concrete briefing room in 1993 InGen service quarters, folding chairs in three rows, a man in a dark green rain jacket at a metal lectern with a clipboard, fluorescent light overhead."}, "The briefing room had no windows. It had concrete walls, a concrete floor, three uneven ranks of folding chairs, a metal lectern bolted to the floor, and a sign over the lectern that said NO RECORDING in English and <i>NO GRABACIÓN</i> in Spanish.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} sat in the second row.", "There were eleven other contractors in the room. They wore coveralls in three colors: green for sanitation, gray for maintenance, tan for food service. There was nobody in white. White was for the laboratory, and the laboratory did not come to this briefing.", "He looked at the men around him. The three other green coveralls were on his row. One of them was older than the others. One of them had a scar at the corner of his mouth where a tooth had once been knocked through. The third was a kid, twenty maybe, with the kind of haircut a barber gave a man who could not afford to come back twice. The gray coveralls were behind him. The tan coveralls were in the front row, including Paola Ruiz, who was at the far end, with her hands flat on her knees and her eyes on the lectern.", "The room smelled of cement that had been wet, then dried, then wet again, in the cycle a building got into when its dehumidifier had not been serviced.", "At 06:00 exactly, {{Robert Muldoon}} came into the room.", "He was a tall man. He was the kind of tall that had been earned at age fourteen and not gotten any taller. His rain jacket was a color of green that nobody had ordered for fashion. His boots had been wet for years. He had a face that did not change shape much when he spoke.", "He carried a clipboard and set it on the lectern. He gave no name. He did not look up at the contractors. He turned the first page of the clipboard and read.", "\"No entry to live zones without a handler,\" Robert Muldoon said.", "He paused. He turned the page.", "\"No deviation from authorized routes.\"", "He paused. He turned the page.", "\"No photography. No personal cameras. No personal recorders. No drawings of the facility. No notes on personnel. No notes on animals.\"", "He paused.", "\"If you hear an alarm you move to the nearest green-striped wall and you stay there. You do not move until a handler with a working radio tells you to move. A handler without a working radio is not a handler at that moment. He is a man in the same room as you.\"", "The man two seats from Mateo Valverde shifted in his chair. He was the gray-coveralled man with the missing tooth, and he shifted the way a man shifted when he had heard a sentence and recognized in it a thing that had been true on a different island.", "\"If a door is red-tagged you do not open it. You do not open it if you have access. You do not open it if you have been told to clean it. You do not open it if a man is shouting on the other side of it. You do not open it if a manager who outranks me tells you to open it, because no manager who outranks me will tell you to open a red-tagged door.\"", "He paused for the third time.", "A contractor in gray coveralls in the back row raised a hand.", "The contractor was bald. He had freckles across the back of his hand, and the freckles had been there a long time. He raised the hand the way men raised hands at meetings where the chair was not their friend.", "Robert Muldoon looked up from the clipboard for the first time.", "\"What if we don't follow the rules,\" the contractor in gray said.", "The room did not move.", "Robert Muldoon looked at the contractor in gray for a beat. He looked at the clipboard for a beat. He looked at the contractor again.", "\"That's a question for your next employer,\" Robert Muldoon said.", "He turned the clipboard over and tucked it under his arm.", "He walked out of the briefing room.", "The contractor in gray did not raise his hand again.", "For a few seconds nobody stood up. Mateo Valverde looked at the lectern, which was empty, and then at the row of contractors in front of him, which had not moved, and then at Paola Ruiz, who was still looking at the lectern as if the lectern might say one more thing. It did not. Somebody coughed. The cough released the room. The contractors stood up one by one and filed out the way they had filed in, except slower.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A long beige service corridor in 1993 InGen back-of-house, yellow floor tape, a steel door with a black analog card reader, a worker in green coveralls and one in a white lab coat passing in opposite directions."}, "At 06:24, Mateo Valverde was sent to find a janitorial supply closet in corridor C-7. The wall map said it was a six-minute walk if a man did not get lost.", "He got lost at the second junction, where the corridor split into one with green floor tape and one with yellow, and the wall sign that should have told him which was which was missing. The screw holes in the cinderblock were fresh. The paint around the holes was a slightly different color than the paint around the rest of the wall, the way a painter touched up a wall when he had taken something off it that morning. He stood at the junction with his green badge in his hand and looked at the holes.", "A door behind him opened.", "A man in a white lab coat stepped out into the corridor. He was thin. He was Asian. He held a folder against his chest with one hand and a lidless coffee cup in the other. He moved the way a man moved when his next twenty minutes had already been promised to someone else.", "He stopped because Mateo Valverde was standing in front of the door reader on the other side of the corridor.", "The man in the white lab coat had a name tag. The name tag said HENRY WU, PH.D.", "Henry Wu looked at the green badge.", "\"Temporary sanitation,\" Henry Wu said.", "\"Yes,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Henry Wu glanced at the door reader. He glanced at the corridor behind Mateo Valverde. He took a small breath, in the way of a man who had been told earlier in the morning to spend less time on certain conversations.", "\"The {{raptors}}' metabolic waste has high pathogen load,\" Henry Wu said. \"Don't let it contact broken skin.\"", "He paused.", "\"For your sake, obviously. Not theirs.\"", "The smile that went with the sentence was a small smile, and it did not stay long. It was the smile of a man who had once enjoyed making jokes of this kind to other men in white coats and had stopped, gradually, because the jokes had stopped landing the way jokes were supposed to land.", "Henry Wu was already moving past him. He stepped past Mateo Valverde and held his own white identification card to the reader. The reader clicked green at once. The door opened. Henry Wu went through the door. The door closed with a soft hydraulic sigh, and the lock engaged, and the corridor was again the way it had been before the door had opened, except for one thing.", "The reader on Mateo Valverde's side of the corridor had also turned green.", "The reason for that was not clear to him.", "He looked at the green badge in his hand. He looked at the reader. The green light blinked once and then steadied. The blink was the kind of blink a reader gave when it had decided that a person was authorized.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A worker in green coveralls stands alone at a steel door with a beige analog card reader glowing green, a temporary badge in one hand, fluorescent corridor light reflecting on wet boots."}, "Mateo Valverde stood at the reader for what he later understood to have been forty seconds. He stood the way a man stood at the door of a church he was not from.", "The reader stayed green.", "Behind him, somebody hit a cart against a wall and swore in English.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the door.", "The door was a steel door. The door had a small wired-glass window at eye height. Through the window he could see a longer corridor, beige walls, a row of mop buckets, a hand truck, and at the far end of the corridor a second door with a red tag hanging from the handle.", "He looked at the red tag.", "He could not read what was on the red tag from this far away.", "He thought about Robert Muldoon's clipboard. He thought about the sentence about the red tag, which had been long, and clear, and had no exceptions in it. He thought about the green light on the reader, which was an exception nobody had told him about.", "He looked at the green light on the reader.", "He looked back at the door.", "He opened the door."], "epigraph": {"text": "He said the animals don't go near that building. He said it twice.", "attribution": "— Paola Ruiz, kitchen staff"}},
  7: {"n": 7, "title": "Chapter 7: Temporary Badge", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A back-office InGen contractor desk in 1993, wet boots on beige tile, cheap paperwork, a green temporary badge under a laminator, storm clouds visible through a small jalousie window."}, "It had been nine days since {{Jophery Brown}} died when {{Mateo Valverde}} signed the temporary contract.", "The contract was in English first and Spanish second. The English took up more space. The Spanish used smaller letters, and some of the words in the Spanish were not the words Mateo Valverde would have used if he had been explaining the same thing to his mother. <i>Riesgo biológico</i>. <i>Acceso limitado</i>. <i>Subcontratista temporal</i>. The paper made the work sound like the work at Hospital San Juan de Dios, except the hourly number was not a hospital number, and the company logo at the top was a red-and-black dinosaur skeleton inside a shield.", "Mateo Valverde had read the number twice.", "Then he signed.", "The man across the desk was Dale Haskins. Dale Haskins had a red face, a wet contractor cap, and a forearm that had missed two places with sunscreen. He smelled of coffee and old rain. He had not sat down since Mateo arrived. He leaned over the desk as if sitting would make the meeting too official, and as if standing kept it the kind of meeting a man could leave from quickly.", "\"Two weeks,\" Dale Haskins said. \"Maybe less. Maybe more. Depends on whether the regular team clears.\"", "\"Regular team,\" Mateo said.", "\"Private animal-control contractors. Security-certified. Former military, most of them. They don't have anyone available this week who can travel under the confidentiality rules.\"", "Mateo looked at the second page of the contract. There were four places where he had initialed. One of them said he understood that all waste encountered on {{Isla Nublar}} belonged to InGen. Another said that any item found in the course of his work — clothing, equipment, personal effects — was likewise InGen property. A third said that no medical claim arising from his work would be filed in any court of any jurisdiction except the one named on a fourth page he had not yet been given.", "\"I am not animal control,\" Mateo said.", "Dale Haskins laughed once.", "\"Nobody said you were. You clean. You bag. You don't open animal doors. You don't touch fences. You don't ask questions in front of guests. You see blood, you treat it like blood. You see tissue, you treat it like tissue. You see anything with teeth still attached, you call the handler.\"", "He slid a plastic badge across the desk.", "The badge was green. The photograph on it had been taken ten minutes earlier under fluorescent light, with Mateo's hair still wet from the rain at the dock. Under the photograph it said:", "MATEO VALVERDE TEMPORARY CONTRACTOR SANITATION / BIOHAZARD VALID: FOURTEEN DAYS", "\"Don't lose that,\" Dale Haskins said. \"You lose that, you don't exist.\"", "Mateo thought it was a joke.", "It was not a funny joke, but men like Dale Haskins made jokes by telling the truth without looking at it. He had said <i>you don't exist</i> in the middle of an exhale, the way a man delivered a line he had practiced on previous workers, and Mateo Valverde understood that the joke had been told before, and that the joke had been told to the previous holder of the slot, and that the previous holder of the slot had ceased to exist by the rules of that joke before he had ceased to exist by other rules.", "He clipped the badge to his coveralls.", "The plastic of the clip was warm from the laminator.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Mateo Valverde, a tired Costa Rican temporary sanitation contractor in off-white InGen facilities coveralls, holding a green temporary badge beside a wet staff-only corridor, analog reader glowing green."}, "The first door opened.", "Mateo held the badge to the reader beside the contractor office. The reader was a square beige box with a red light and a green light and a speaker grille full of dust. The green light blinked. The lock clicked. Dale Haskins pointed with his chin.", "\"See? You're official.\"", "Behind the door was not the park from the brochure.", "Behind the door was a service corridor with beige walls, yellow floor tape, mop buckets, a hand truck, a row of rubber boots, and a laminated sign that said STAFF ONLY in English and Spanish. The air smelled of bleach, wet cardboard, and something sweet underneath, something the heat had spoiled. The bleach was the bleach a building used when it had decided that smell was a kind of evidence and had to be killed first.", "A man in a dark green rain jacket passed them carrying a rifle pointed at the floor. He glanced once at Mateo's badge.", "\"New temp?\" he said.", "\"Sanitation,\" Dale Haskins said.", "The man with the rifle looked at Mateo's hands.", "\"Keep him out of live zones.\"", "\"He's not stupid.\"", "\"Didn't ask that.\"", "The man with the rifle kept walking. He walked the way men walked when they had not been thanked at the start of any of their last forty days, and would not be thanked at the end of any of their next forty days, and had stopped expecting that the count of unthanked days would matter to anyone but them.", "Mateo watched him go. The rifle was not clean. There was rust-colored dirt in the seam near the sling mount. Not old dirt. Wet dirt.", "\"That is security?\" Mateo asked.", "\"Asset containment,\" Dale Haskins said.", "\"With rifles.\"", "\"With procedures.\"", "They walked.", "The corridor opened into a staff canteen. Men in boots sat at plastic tables eating from metal trays. Some wore InGen patches. Some wore contractor patches. Some wore no patches at all, only field shirts with the sleeves rolled tight over large forearms. They spoke in English, mostly. They used words Mateo knew from American movies and did not like hearing over lunch: perimeter, sector, extraction, hot, cold, clean, dirty.", "No one at the tables looked surprised to see another worker.", "No one looked pleased.", "Mateo stood with his lunch tray and understood, before anyone said it, that every seat had a rank.", "He took the chair nearest the trash bins.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "An InGen staff canteen behind the visitor areas, plastic tables, ex-military contractors in wet field gear, Mateo alone near trash bins with his temporary badge bright against dull coveralls."}, "That afternoon, {{Tomás Araya}} gave him the real orientation.", "Tomás Araya was the senior sanitation tech. He had worked construction camps, port cold storage, hotel kitchens, and one government clinic where the drains had backed up into surgery during the rainy season. He had a permanent badge, a mustache stained at the middle, and a flashlight wrapped in black tape. He had a way of walking through a corridor that meant he had decided in advance which seams in the floor were going to be his problem and which were going to be somebody else's.", "\"Haskins told you the rules,\" Tomás Araya said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Good. Forget half. Remember the half that keeps your fingers.\"", "Tomás walked him through the waste route with no brochure language. Meat prep. Animal laundry. Staff toilets. Dock corridor. Medical cold room. {{Raptor}} service washdown. Storm drain cutoff. Dirty gear side. Clean gear side. Locker room. Chemical cage.", "He named each in two breaths. He pointed to each with two fingers. He did not slow at any of them, the way a man did not slow at the doors of rooms whose contents he wanted to forget on the way home.", "\"You see green tape on a door, it means someone fixed it.\"", "\"And yellow?\"", "\"It means someone wants to remember to fix it.\"", "\"And red?\"", "Tomás stopped at the end of the corridor. A steel door stood there with a red tag hanging from the handle. The tag had been printed on a small dot-matrix printer. The ink had run a little at the bottom. Underneath the tag, the metal of the door had a faint rectangular outline where another tag had hung before this one and had been removed for replacement, and replaced again, and replaced again, in the cycle a door got into when the kind of fix it needed had not yet been invented.", "\"Red means a manager signed a paper saying it was fixed.\"", "Mateo looked at the door.", "The door looked closed.", "Behind it, something struck metal once. Not hard. Testing.", "Tomás stayed where he was.", "Mateo stayed where he was.", "The steel door stayed closed.", "A second tap came. The same tap. The same testing pressure. It was not the tap of a tool that had fallen. It was the tap of a thing that wanted to know whether the door was alive.", "Tomás Araya did not look at the door. He looked at the corridor wall, which had no decoration. He looked at the laminated sign at the corridor turn, which was not missing, and the screw holes for which were not fresh.", "\"Raptor service is tomorrow night,\" Tomás Araya said.", "Mateo Valverde looked at his green badge.", "The plastic was still clean."]},
  8: {"n": 8, "title": "Chapter 8: The Places Guests Don't See", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "An original 1993 InGen service map spread on a wet utility cart, hand-marked waste routes, staff-only corridors, dock arrows, raptor service area circled in pencil."}, "By the fifth day, {{Mateo Valverde}} knew the park by smell.", "The visitor center smelled of new stone, cold air, and expensive varnish if a person came in through the front. Mateo Valverde had never come in through the front. From behind, the same building smelled of fryer oil, cardboard boxes, bleach water, and the warm sour breath of garbage compactors waiting for parts from the mainland.", "The dock corridor smelled of diesel.", "The medical cold room smelled of alcohol and plastic.", "The maintenance tunnel under the east service road smelled of wet concrete and old batteries, and of a sweet thin smell underneath, the smell of a small animal that had died in a wall and that nobody who knew the wall was going to mention.", "The {{raptor}} service bay smelled different every day.", "That was the first thing {{Tomás Araya}} taught him.", "\"Do not get used to it,\" Tomás Araya said.", "They stood outside the bay with rubber aprons over their coveralls. Tomás Araya had wrapped his sleeves twice with tape. Mateo Valverde had copied him.", "\"You mean the smell?\"", "\"I mean anything. This place changes its habits and then expects you to have known.\"", "The door reader blinked green when Tomás Araya used his permanent badge. It blinked green when Mateo Valverde used his temporary badge. The second green light mattered to Mateo Valverde more than he wanted it to. He had begun to learn which men looked through him and which men looked at the badge first. The badge made some of them let him pass. The badge did not make him belong.", "The first day, Tomás Araya had taken him through every door at the inner ring without giving him the names of the rooms behind those doors. The second day, Tomás Araya had given him the names. The third day, he had taken him through the rooms whose names he had given. The fourth day, he had told Mateo Valverde which rooms he should never have entered. The fifth day was for the raptor service bay, which Tomás Araya had been holding for last, the way a man held the worst job for the day his apprentice had stopped flinching at the noise the lock made when it caught.", "Inside, the bay was empty of animals.", "That was what the orientation said.", "Empty meant no animal body was currently visible from the safe side of the reinforced line. Empty did not mean quiet. Empty did not mean clean. Empty did not mean the air was free of what had been there.", "Hose reels hung on one wall. Biohazard bags stood in a yellow bin. Straw and feed waste clung to the grated trench that ran along the floor. The concrete sloped toward a drain sump with a steel cover bolted down at four corners. One bolt was missing. Someone had circled the empty hole with yellow paint.", "\"Red tag?\" Mateo Valverde asked.", "\"Yellow paint is cheaper,\" Tomás Araya said.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A wet concrete raptor waste service bay, yellow emergency lights, hose reels, grated trench drain, red biohazard bags, straw and meat waste caught in the grate."}, "The work was not complicated.", "First, rinse the outer floor. Second, collect straw. Third, scrape solids into the biohazard bin. Fourth, flush the trench. Fifth, record volume by bag count, not by weight, because the scale had been waiting on a replacement part for eleven days.", "Mateo Valverde did the work.", "The men with rifles did not watch him do it. They watched the doors, the mesh, the corners, the places a person looked if a thing might come through. Mateo Valverde watched the floor.", "The floor told him more than the men did.", "Three days earlier the animal had eaten beef. The hair in the waste was short and black and mixed with straw. The day after that, the waste had more feathers because someone had tried poultry enrichment. The day after that, the waste had not been cleaned properly because the inspection team had been moved through the visitor side and every spare person had been sent to polish glass.", "On the fifth day, there was cloth in the grate.", "Not much. A strip as long as two fingers, dark blue under the brown. Mateo Valverde caught it on the scraper and held it up.", "The cloth was not torn. It was cut. The edge was the edge of fabric that had been cut against a hard surface by something that did not have a blade in the way a blade was a blade. He turned it on the scraper. The reverse side had a piece of stitched seam, the kind of seam that ran along the inside of a uniform sleeve. The thread of the seam was machine-thread, white, not the color the dye had ended up.", "Tomás Araya saw it.", "\"Bag it,\" Tomás Araya said.", "\"It is fabric.\"", "\"From uniforms?\"", "Tomás Araya turned the hose toward the trench.", "\"Do you want to work here tomorrow?\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at the fabric. He looked at Tomás Araya. He looked at the trench, where the water was already running brown and would not be brown by the time anyone above this bay heard about the strip of cloth, because Tomás Araya had set the hose on the <i>full</i> setting, and the <i>full</i> setting on this hose moved a problem out of a bay in less than ninety seconds.", "He bagged it.", "He pulled the bag closed with both hands. He did not look at it again. He set the bag on the cart with the other bags. He marked the count on the form on the cart, in the small box for that hour, with the pencil that hung from the cart on a string.", "Tomás Araya did not say anything.", "After that, Mateo Valverde began drawing his own map.", "Not the map for guests. Not the map with tour roads and fences and pretty icons of animals. Mateo Valverde drew the map that mattered to waste: where carts could turn, where a hose could reach, where a door needed a shoulder, where the floor dropped half an inch and filled with water when it rained.", "He used the backs of safety data sheets and a pencil stolen from the canteen. He drew the map every night before he slept, in the bunkroom, with the fluorescent light off and the corner-strip light on. The corner-strip light was steady enough to draw by if a man did not look at it directly. He drew the map small. He folded the map four ways and kept it in the inside breast pocket of his coveralls, behind the badge.", "Tomás Araya saw the map on the third night and laughed through his nose.", "\"You think they don't have maps?\"", "\"I think I do not have their maps.\"", "Tomás Araya stopped laughing.", "\"Good answer.\"", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Mateo marking a handmade staff-route map on the back of a chemical safety sheet, utility corridor pipes and analog warning signs behind him."}, "The park had two versions of every place.", "There was the kitchen where guests would see steaks and cakes and red tablecloths. Behind that kitchen was the prep room where a side of beef could arrive bleeding through the paper because the thaw schedule had been changed twice, and where a man could stand at the back-wall sink and run his hands under cold water for a minute that the kitchen above did not know about, because the second-version places of the park did not show up on the same clocks.", "There was the visitor center with the skeletons. Beneath it was the service level where the tour vehicles slept and where a lift door stuck open unless a person kicked the lower track.", "There was the raptor pen from the outside, all fear and steel.", "Behind it, there was the washdown bay, the gear hallway, the clean-change corridor, the locker room, the chemical cage, and the access-control closet where a beige terminal sat on a folding table with a sign taped to it:", "DO NOT POWER CYCLE WITHOUT AUTHORIZATION.", "Someone had written below it in black marker:", "THEN FIX IT.", "On the ninth day, Evelyn Park found Mateo Valverde reading the sign.", "She was small, wet-haired, and younger than the voice she used on the radio. Her glasses had rain spots on them. A pager hung from her belt beside a ring of keys and two badge blanks. She wore a sweatshirt under her InGen IT vest, and the sweatshirt had the logo of a college that was not on Costa Rica's list of colleges. Her hands were small and red at the cuticles in the way the hands of people who typed on cheap keyboards in cold rooms got red at the cuticles.", "\"You need that room?\" Evelyn Park asked.", "\"Then don't need it.\"", "\"The reader outside sticks.\"", "\"The reader outside is older than my little brother.\"", "\"It worked.\"", "\"It works when the server likes you.\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at his badge.", "Evelyn Park followed the glance.", "\"Don't worry,\" Evelyn Park said. \"Temps are in the live table. If your face is on that badge, the system knows you.\"", "\"And if the system does not know me?\"", "Evelyn Park smiled, but not very much.", "\"Then stand near someone important.\"", "The pager on her belt chirped. She looked down. Her smile went away. The smile had been small and the going-away of it was small too, but the smile had been the only soft thing in this corridor for the four days Mateo Valverde had been walking it, and he registered the going-away of it the way a man registered a light going off in a building he was about to enter.", "\"Storm meeting,\" Evelyn Park said.", "\"Bad enough they're pretending it isn't.\"", "She went through the access-control door. The reader gave her a green light before the badge had fully touched the plastic.", "Mateo Valverde watched the door close.", "Behind him, past two more corridors and one locked gate, the raptor service bay waited for the next washdown.", "He thought about the strip of dark blue cloth.", "He thought about the hose on the <i>full</i> setting.", "He thought about the seam of machine-thread, and the way Tomás Araya had not looked at the bag once Mateo Valverde had closed it, and the way the water had run brown for a minute and then run clear.", "He took the map from his breast pocket.", "He added a small mark by the trench at the raptor service bay.", "He folded the map again and put it back.", "He went to find a cart."]},
  9: {"n": 9, "title": "Chapter 9: Five-Minute Closure", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Storm rain hammering a staff-only loading bay on Isla Nublar, evacuation carts and wet clipboards abandoned near yellow floor tape, Mateo in sanitation coveralls pushing a utility cart."}, "At 6:31 p.m., the last shuttle call came through the service speakers.", "The speaker above the {{raptor}} washdown bay had a crack across its plastic cover. {{Mateo Valverde}} had cleaned that crack with a toothbrush two nights earlier because Dale Haskins said the investors noticed dust in places investors had no business looking. The speaker made every announcement sound as if the person talking had a hand over his mouth.", "<i>All nonessential staff report to east transport. Repeat, all nonessential staff report to east transport.</i>", "{{Tomás Araya}} looked up from the drain trench.", "\"That means us,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"That means them,\" Tomás Araya said.", "He pointed with his chin toward the corridor, where two security men in rain gear passed without slowing. One carried a rifle. The other carried a waterproof case with red tape around it. Neither looked into the washdown bay.", "Mateo Valverde had both gloves inside the trench. Straw, meat scraps, and disinfectant foam clung to his sleeves. The drain had backed up because the stormwater line outside was already taking more water than it wanted. Five minutes, Dale Haskins had said. A five-minute closure. Tie the bags, flush the trench, secure the sump, get on the shuttle.", "It had been seventeen minutes.", "The raptors were still contained.", "Everyone said that as if it solved every other problem.", "Contained did not make the trench drain. Contained did not move the bags. Contained did not make the meat smell less sweet in the wet air. Contained did not make Mateo Valverde's badge dry.", "Outside the bay, the wind in the corridor had a new sound. It was not the wind of weather coming in. It was the wind of a building that had been told to seal certain doors and had begun to do so. Mateo Valverde had not heard the building make that sound before. He had heard it make many sounds. He had not heard this one.", "Tomás Araya pulled the last red bag from the bin and twisted the top.", "\"Go,\" Tomás Araya said.", "\"We are not done.\"", "\"You are temporary. Temporary means go when the boat is leaving.\"", "Tomás Araya tied the bag. His old permanent badge swung against his apron. It was scratched almost white at the edges.", "\"I have one more room.\"", "Mateo Valverde did not like that answer.", "Tomás Araya saw his face and shook his head.", "\"Don't make a speech. Take the cart to the clean side. Wash your boots. If Haskins asks, I sent you.\"", "The speaker cracked again.", "<i>East transport departing in twenty minutes.</i>", "Mateo Valverde pulled his gloves from the trench.", "Something hard struck his knuckle.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Mateo kneeling beside a raptor waste drain sump, hose water and disinfectant foam swirling around straw, meat scraps, and a half-hidden laminated badge."}, "At first he thought it was a bolt.", "The missing bolt from the sump cover had been annoying him all week. He had looked for it with the long grabber tool and found nothing but straw and the strip of blue cloth. If he found the bolt now, at least one small stupid thing would be complete before the island came apart.", "He pushed two fingers into the foam and pinched the hard edge.", "It was not a bolt.", "It was a badge.", "The plastic had gone cloudy. The clip slot was full of a brown matter that had set into the channels and dried, then gotten wet again. The lanyard was gone except for one torn thread hardened into the laminate. The clip itself was bent at the angle a clip bent at when force had been applied to it from a direction the clip had not been designed to receive. Mateo Valverde wiped the face with the cleanest part of his glove and saw one eye first, then a nose, then a name printed in black under the InGen logo.", "BROWN, JOPHERY RAPTOR SERVICE / PERMANENT STAFF", "Mateo Valverde stopped breathing through his mouth.", "He looked at the photograph on the badge. The photograph showed a man in his early thirties with a half-smile of the kind men wore in ID photos when the man behind the camera had said <i>say something</i>. The man on the badge had said something. The man on the badge had said it under fluorescent light, on a day when his hair had not yet been wet from anything bad.", "Tomás Araya saw the badge in Mateo Valverde's hand.", "For one second the older man did not move. His face went the color of the inside of a pot that had not been used for a long time. His mouth, under the mustache, became smaller. The way Tomás Araya had stopped moving was the way a man stopped moving when he had been told a thing on a phone and had set the phone down and had walked into a hallway and had not yet decided which direction in the hallway was forward.", "Then Tomás Araya crossed the bay faster than Mateo Valverde had ever seen him cross any room.", "\"Bag it,\" Tomás Araya said.", "\"This is his.\"", "\"It was in the drain.\"", "The way Tomás Araya said his name was worse than shouting.", "Mateo Valverde looked from the badge to the drain sump. The foam slid around the grate. Something pale and fibrous clung under the steel lip and then vanished as water pulled it down. He had seen the same fiber in the trench three days ago. He had not asked then. He did not ask now.", "\"They said he was injured,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Tomás Araya took a breath through his nose.", "\"They say many things.\"", "The speaker popped again.", "<i>All remaining nonessential staff, report now. East transport holding for five minutes.</i>", "Five minutes.", "The same lie in a different room.", "The wall phone rang.", "Tomás Araya and Mateo Valverde both looked at it because the wall phone had not rung once in nine days.", "Tomás Araya picked up. He listened. He said, \"Yes.\" He listened again. He looked at Mateo Valverde. \"He found it.\"", "The phone made a small tinny voice.", "Tomás Araya said, \"No. Not in a bag. It has a name.\"", "The voice became sharper.", "Tomás Araya closed his eyes.", "\"Understood.\"", "He hung up.", "\"Haskins?\" Mateo Valverde asked.", "\"Haskins says secure it in the locker. Clean side. He will collect after evacuation.\"", "\"We should give it to someone.\"", "\"Everyone is someone right now.\"", "Tomás Araya took a clear evidence sleeve from the cabinet, the kind they used for broken sharps. He held it open. Mateo Valverde dropped the badge inside. The sleeve sealed with a small zip sound.", "It looked clean in the plastic.", "That made it worse.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Jophery Brown's old permanent InGen badge sealed in a clear evidence sleeve, grime caught in the clip, Mateo's wet glove holding it under yellow emergency light."}, "The route to the locker room was short.", "Dirty bay. Gear hooks. Boot wash. Clean-change hallway. Locker room. Staff corridor. Shuttle point.", "Mateo Valverde knew that route better than any guest knew the tour road. He had walked it carrying bags, mops, broken hoses, crates of disinfectant, and once a bucket with a dead chicken in it because the feed team had put the wrong label on the wrong bin.", "He could walk it in three minutes if no door stuck.", "The first door opened with Tomás Araya's badge.", "The second door opened with Mateo Valverde's badge.", "Green light. Click. Green light. Click.", "His badge worked. His badge had always worked.", "Tomás Araya stayed on the dirty side. He did not say goodbye. He had said goodbye once at the dock the morning Mateo Valverde had arrived, and had not said it since. A man who had said goodbye once did not need to say it twice in nine days.", "\"Go,\" Tomás Araya said.", "\"You said that already.\"", "\"And you are still here.\"", "Mateo Valverde put the evidence sleeve under his arm and stepped into the clean-change hallway. The door closed behind him. The hallway was narrow, tiled, and too bright. On the left were the dirty lockers. On the right were the clean lockers. At the far end was the staff corridor door, beyond which the shuttle point waited in rain.", "Mateo Valverde opened locker 18.", "{{Jophery Brown}}'s name was still taped inside.", "Not on the outside. InGen had removed the outside label. Inside, behind the hanging hook, a strip of tape remained with J. BROWN written in black marker. The letters were neat and square. The way the letters were neat and square was the way a man wrote his own name on a strip of tape on the day he received a permanent locker, when the tape had been new, and the marker had been new, and a man's hands had been steady, and a man had thought he had a long time to use the locker.", "The hook had a wire hanger on it.", "The shelf had a coffee-cup ring of the kind that did not come off plastic.", "The back of the locker had a small piece of folded paper taped to it that said <i>ABBY CALL SAT</i> with a phone number.", "Mateo Valverde put the sleeve on the shelf, beside the coffee ring.", "He stood in front of the open locker with his hand on the door.", "He thought about the sister.", "He thought about Saturday.", "He thought about the cardboard backing of the shaving kit, which he had not been told about and would not be told about, but which was the kind of thing a man like Jophery Brown would have done.", "The lights flickered once.", "The ventilation stopped.", "Somewhere beyond the wall, the park made a sound Mateo Valverde had never heard before.", "Not a roar.", "Not an alarm.", "A silence turning on."]},
  10: {"n": 10, "title": "Chapter 10: Jophery Brown", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A narrow clean-change locker hallway in 1993 InGen service infrastructure, fluorescent lights flickering, wet boot prints, one open locker with J. BROWN written on tape inside."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} did not move for six seconds.", "He knew because the clock above the clean lockers still worked. It had a red second hand that jumped instead of swept. The hand clicked from twelve to one, from one to two, from two to three. Six clicks before Mateo Valverde remembered the shuttle.", "Then he moved.", "He shut {{Jophery Brown}}'s locker. He wiped his gloves on his apron because the evidence sleeve had been clean and the rest of him was not. He crossed the clean-change hallway and put his badge to the staff corridor reader.", "The reader did nothing.", "Mateo Valverde lifted the badge away and tried again.", "The red light blinked.", "He had seen red before. Red when he tried {{Tomás Araya}}'s chemical cage by mistake. Red when he held the badge too low. Red when rainwater got between the plastic and the reader. Red was not disaster. Red was a request to do it correctly.", "Mateo Valverde wiped the badge on his coverall.", "He pressed it flat.", "Red.", "Behind him, the dirty-side door clicked.", "That door had been locked since he came in. It clicked now not like an opening door, but like a door checking itself, the way a door checked itself when the building had decided to remember the door's lock and had to confirm what its current state was supposed to be.", "Mateo Valverde turned.", "The dirty-side reader showed no light at all.", "\"Tomás?\"", "No answer.", "He pressed the staff corridor intercom button.", "The speaker gave him three seconds of voices.", "<i>...vehicles are stopped...</i>", "<i>...not the {{raptor}} fences, I said...</i>", "<i>...east transport final...</i>", "Then a burst of static filled the hallway so loudly Mateo Valverde stepped back.", "The static cut off.", "The hallway became small.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Close-up of Mateo's green temporary contractor badge pressed to a beige analog InGen badge reader, red light reflected in a wet glove, dead wall phone hanging nearby."}, "Mateo Valverde tried the badge six more times.", "The seventh time the little beige display below the reader woke up. He had not known the reader had a display. A line of green letters dragged themselves across the black strip one by one.", "LOCAL SAFE MODE ACTIVE", "He did not understand the words at first.", "He understood <i>safe</i>.", "That was the wrong word.", "The display changed.", "NETWORK CREDENTIAL TABLE UNAVAILABLE", "Then:", "CREDENTIAL NOT FOUND", "Mateo Valverde looked at his own photograph in the plastic badge. The photograph looked tired and flat under the laminate. The badge said his name. The machine said it did not.", "\"No,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "It was not a word for anyone else. It was a word the way men said <i>no</i> in their sleep, automatically, against a thing in a dream that had gotten close enough to need a word against it.", "He tried the dirty-side door.", "Red.", "He tried the staff corridor door.", "Red.", "He tried the wall phone. The receiver was still there, bolted to a metal cord. It had no dial, only three square buttons: CONTROL, SECURITY, MEDICAL. He pressed CONTROL. Nothing. SECURITY. Nothing. MEDICAL gave him a click and then the sound of someone breathing.", "\"Hello?\"", "The breathing continued.", "\"This is sanitation. Clean-change hallway by raptor service. I am locked in.\"", "The breathing became voices in the distance, not one person, many people. A man said, \"Hold on to your butts,\" far away and half-buried in static. The voice that said it was tired in a way that did not match the words. It was the voice of a man who had said something difficult by saying something easy, and was about to push a button he did not want to push.", "Then the line died.", "Mateo Valverde held the receiver until the dead tone began.", "He hung the receiver up.", "The clock clicked seven more seconds.", "The shuttle would not wait for a temporary worker in a clean-change hallway.", "He opened Jophery Brown's locker again.", "The evidence sleeve lay on the shelf.", "Jophery Brown's badge looked up from inside the plastic.", "Mateo Valverde did not touch it.", "Not yet.", "He searched the locker first because searching was not stealing. Searching was work. Searching was procedure. A sanitation contractor who had been told to secure a thing in a locker had a reason to look in the locker. A man who had been forgotten by a building had a reason to look at a man whom the building remembered.", "There was an old towel. A cracked comb. Two green uniform shirts folded badly. A packet of aspirin. A photograph of a woman and a boy at a picnic table, the boy holding a paper cup with both hands. The woman in the photograph had a soft face and a sweater pushed up to her elbows, and the boy had been told to look at the camera and was looking at the cup. The photograph had been taken somewhere green. There were no Costa Rican trees in it.", "A laminated cleaning checklist with three boxes marked in blue pen.", "At the bottom, behind one boot, was a folded route sheet.", "Mateo Valverde opened it.", "It was not an official map. It was better.", "Jophery Brown had drawn the raptor service block by hand. Not pretty. Not to scale. Useful. Door numbers. Reader types. Drain access. Ceiling panels. Manual releases. One note written beside the clean-change hallway:", "OLD READER. HATES NEW CARDS.", "Mateo Valverde laughed once.", "It came out wrong. It came out like a sound a man made when his shoulders had been held too tight for too long and the muscle had decided to release without asking.", "He looked at his own folded map in his breast pocket.", "The two maps were of the same building.", "The clock clicked.", "Then the dirty-side door reader chirped.", "Mateo Valverde froze.", "No one had touched it.", "The display blinked:", "LOCAL SAFE MODE ACTIVE", "Then:", "BROWN, JOPHERY - SERVICE AUTHORIZED", "The door did not open.", "The reader chirped again, as if waiting.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Jophery Brown's old permanent badge on a locker shelf beside a handmade raptor service route map, fluorescent light flickering over the name."}, "Mateo Valverde put his hand on the evidence sleeve.", "He took it away.", "He wiped his glove on his apron, slow, because the apron was not clean and the glove was not clean and the slowness gave him something to do that was not the next thing.", "He looked at the photograph of the woman and the boy with the paper cup.", "He looked at the strip of tape with J. BROWN in black marker, neat, square, written on a day when a man had thought he had time.", "He looked at his own green badge clipped to his coverall, the laminate fogged at the edge where his thumb had pressed it against the reader six times.", "The clock clicked.", "His right hand reached the sleeve again. The plastic was thin between his fingers. He could feel the shape of the badge inside, the clip slot, the broken edge of the lanyard hole. His thumbnail caught the seam.", "He stopped.", "Tomás Araya had said <i>bag it</i>. Dale Haskins had said <i>secure it</i>. Both men had said the same thing using different words. Both men had said it as if the badge belonged to a paper trail that someone else would walk down later.", "There was no later anymore. There was a hallway, and two red lights, and a clock with a jumping second hand, and a man on a phone breathing into a receiver before he pushed a button.", "Jophery Brown was dead.", "The machine remembered Jophery Brown.", "Mateo Valverde was alive.", "The machine had forgotten him.", "His thumbnail found the seam again.", "He thought about the sister. <i>ABBY CALL SAT.</i> He thought about the photograph and the paper cup and the green country he could not name. He thought about the men who had pulled Jophery Brown out of the mouth of an animal in the rain, and about the man who had pressed a yellow rain poncho against the place where the femoral was no longer, and about whether any of them would say his name now if they saw what he was about to do.", "He tore open the evidence sleeve.", "The plastic made a sound too loud for the hallway.", "He wiped Jophery Brown's badge with the towel. The towel had been folded badly because Jophery Brown had folded it on a night when he had been tired, and a man who had been tired on a night had not been planning to be folded into a steel box on a different night. Mateo Valverde wiped the magnetic stripe until the dried matter came off in brown flakes. He held the old permanent badge to the staff corridor reader.", "Red.", "He held it again.", "Red.", "On the third try, the reader went dark.", "For one bad second Mateo Valverde thought he had broken the only thing in the room that still believed in anyone.", "Then the green light came on.", "The lock clicked.", "The display printed one line.", "BROWN, JOPHERY - STAFF ACCESS", "The staff corridor door opened two inches.", "Mateo Valverde did not go through immediately.", "He looked back at the locker.", "Jophery Brown's towel lay on the bench. The photograph had fallen face down. The route sheet was in Mateo Valverde's left hand. The old badge was in his right.", "He thought, <i>I am sorry.</i>", "He did not say it.", "A man who said <i>I am sorry</i> to a dead man's locker was a man who had decided to keep talking to the dead man, and Mateo Valverde was not yet ready to do that.", "The clock clicked again.", "Mateo Valverde stepped through the door.", "Behind him, the clean-change hallway lights went out."]},
  11: {"n": 11, "title": "Chapter 11: Profile Not Found", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A storm-lashed staff-only service corridor opening toward rain, Mateo running with a handmade route sheet and old permanent badge, exposed pipes and yellow emergency lights behind him."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} ran the wrong way first.", "That was what saved him from believing the park still made sense.", "The staff corridor outside the clean-change hallway should have turned left toward the shuttle point. Mateo Valverde knew this because he had pushed carts through it for nine days. Left, then the boot wash, then the contractor entrance, then the covered path to east transport. Three minutes if the floor was dry. Four if the floor was wet. Five if a manager stopped him to ask why the bags were not labeled with the new stickers.", "Mateo Valverde turned left.", "He could feel the building wrong as he ran. The corridor lights were not all on. The ones that were on were the emergency strips, not the overhead panels, and the emergency strips were the wrong color of yellow, the yellow of a ceiling that had been filmed by a nineteen-eighties camera and looked back at on a bad television. Two of the door readers he passed were dark. One was lit but not blinking, holding a single steady amber light he had never seen before.", "The fire door at the end of the corridor was closed.", "Not locked. Closed was normal. Closed meant push the bar and move. He hit the bar with both hands.", "The door did not move.", "He hit it again.", "Above the bar, a new red tag hung from the latch, swinging in the air from his impact. The tag was not the laminated kind. The tag was paper, printed on a cheap dot-matrix in a font that had not been chosen for fire doors.", "SECURITY DEGRADE AUTO-SEAL ACTIVE", "No one had mentioned auto-seal in orientation.", "No one mentioned many things.", "Mateo Valverde put {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge to the reader. The reader thought for three seconds and gave him a green light.", "The door still did not move.", "Green did not mean open.", "That was the next lesson.", "Behind him, down the corridor he had come from, a PA speaker popped and said half a sentence.", "<i>...East Dock vessel departing at nineteen hundred...</i>", "Then the speaker died.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the red tag. He looked at Jophery Brown's route sheet. The paper was warm from his hand. Jophery Brown's handwriting beside the main corridor said:", "FIRE DOOR FAILS SHUT WHEN NETWORK DROPS.", "Under it, in smaller letters:", "USE LAUNDRY.", "The two notes were written in the same hand, but the second was tighter, pressed in deeper, the way a man wrote down a thing he had needed to remember at four in the morning, when he had walked the long way around once and had decided not to walk it long the next time.", "Mateo Valverde turned around.", "He ran right.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A 1993 InGen corridor fire door with SECURITY DEGRADE AUTO-SEAL ACTIVE tag, green badge reader light useless beside a door that will not open."}, "The laundry route was not on the guest map.", "The laundry route was not on the contractor orientation map either. It ran behind the service toilets, past a linen chute, through a room where damp staff uniforms hung on a pipe rack, then into the back of the kitchen corridor and out toward the shuttle point from the wrong side.", "Mateo Valverde had hated that route because the carts caught on the threshold.", "Now he loved the threshold because no manager had thought to put an auto-seal door there.", "He crossed the uniform room with his shoulder against the wet hanging shirts. The shirts were green and tan, with the patches still on, with name tags on some and not on others. The man who had been told to launder them had not yet been told that nobody on the island would be wearing them tomorrow. The shirts smelled of wet cotton and chlorine and the heat of a dryer that had not run in two hours.", "Someone's radio lay on a folding table. He grabbed it. The battery clip had tape on it, of the kind a worker put on a clip that had cracked once and been repaired by the worker because the parts list for radio clips had been too short to cover a cracked clip. He pressed the side button.", "\"East transport, this is sanitation. Mateo Valverde, {{raptor}} service. I am in the laundry route. Do you copy?\"", "Static.", "\"East transport, this is sanitation.\"", "A voice answered, but not to him.", "<i>Rosa, get those last two pallets off the pier or leave them. We are not holding for cargo.</i>", "The voice was a man's. The voice on the answering side was a woman's. Mateo Valverde did not know either of them.", "He pressed the button again.", "\"Rosa. This is Mateo Valverde. Temporary contractor. I am still on site.\"", "Static.", "Then:", "<i>Say again?</i>", "The voice was sharp. Not unkind. Sharp the way a voice was sharp when it had been holding three radios at once and was used to people calling on the wrong channel.", "\"I am still on site. Raptor service. Badge failure. I am coming to the shuttle point.\"", "The radio hissed.", "<i>Who authorized you to stay?</i>", "Mateo Valverde almost laughed. He did not have enough breath.", "\"No one.\"", "There was a pause on her end of the line. The pause was long enough that Mateo Valverde thought the radio had died.", "<i>Then move.</i>", "He moved.", "He reached the shuttle point at 6:58 p.m.", "The covered pad outside the contractor entrance was empty.", "Not nearly empty.", "Empty.", "A clipboard hung from a nail beside the door, the pages limp with rain, and the top page had Mateo Valverde's name on it in a list of seventeen names with checkmarks beside sixteen and a blank beside his. A plastic sign had blown sideways and now pointed toward a wall. Tire tracks ran through standing water and curved toward the dock road. The water in the tracks was already thinning, which meant the trucks had passed not long ago and not very long ago at all.", "Mateo Valverde ran into the rain.", "The storm took the heat from him in one breath.", "He followed the tire tracks because tire tracks were more honest than signs. Past the staff generator shed, where the diesel was running in the way diesels ran when they had decided to run on their own, without a man at the panel. Past the waste cage, which was not locked. Past the low concrete wall where two days earlier he had seen a guest vehicle roll by clean and empty on its test route. Past a security post with the door open and the chair overturned.", "The road bent.", "He saw the dock lights.", "For three seconds, he thought he had made it.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Storm-lashed East Dock service overlook at night, cargo pallets under tarps, floodlights blurred by rain, the evacuation boat's stern light pulling away while Mateo reaches a chain-link fence too late."}, {"type": "image", "src": "action-1.webp", "alt": "Storm-lashed East Dock service overlook at night, Mateo gripping a chain-link fence as the evacuation boat's stern light recedes into heavy rain, tarps snapping over cargo pallets and floodlights flaring through mist."}, "The boat's stern light moved behind the rain.", "It was small. That was the thing that hurt. Not dramatic. Not close enough to shout to. A small red light, sliding away from the pier while the dark water rose and fell between it and the island. There was no horn. There was no announcement. The boat had simply chosen the moment Mateo Valverde had not yet arrived to be the moment of leaving.", "Mateo Valverde reached the chain-link fence above the service road. His hands struck the metal. Jophery Brown's badge hit the fence and swung from his fingers.", "\"Hey!\"", "The storm took the word.", "\"Hey!\"", "The boat did not slow.", "Below him, on the dock, two figures in rain gear were pulling the last line. One looked back once. Mateo Valverde saw the pale oval of a face under a hood. Maybe Rosa. Maybe not. The figure lifted an arm, not in farewell, not in greeting. A signal to someone on the boat.", "Then the line dropped.", "The boat moved again.", "The red stern light blurred, broke in the rain, and became nothing.", "Mateo Valverde stayed at the fence until his hands hurt.", "He stayed because the alternative was turning away from the fence, and turning away from the fence was the act that admitted what the fence already knew. The fence had known for several minutes. He had not yet caught up to the fence.", "He thought about his mother.", "He thought about the inner tube under the sink eight blocks from her front door.", "He thought about the photograph of the woman and the boy with the paper cup, which had fallen face down in a locker that the building no longer believed was his to look in.", "Behind him, inside the service corridor, a badge reader chirped.", "He turned.", "There was no one by the door.", "The reader chirped again.", "Jophery Brown's name appeared on the little green display.", "WELCOME BACK."]},
  12: {"n": 12, "title": "Chapter 12: Dead Man's Access", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A rain-lashed East Dock service gate after the evacuation boat has gone, yellow work lights on wet concrete, an analog badge reader glowing beside chain-link fence."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} stayed at the fence until the boat light became the same color as the rain.", "Then he made himself count.", "One breath for the dock.", "One breath for the road.", "One breath for the stupid green letters on the reader behind him.", "WELCOME BACK, JOPHERY BROWN.", "He had counted to three because three was as many as a man could count when his hands had stopped working in a useful way and his lungs had begun to ask for breaths smaller than his rib cage was used to giving. He counted again. Three more breaths. Then one. Then he stopped counting.", "Diesel hung under the service awning. The smell tried to convince him the boat would turn. It did not. The east water went black. Dock lines slapped the pilings. Behind the maintenance shed, sheet metal banged once and kept banging, a loose corner working itself free in the storm.", "Mateo Valverde put his own badge to the dock office reader.", "Red.", "He put {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge to the reader.", "Green.", "The lock opened with a clean little click.", "He hated the sound. It was too polite. It sounded as if the park had been waiting for the dead man and was pleased he had kept his appointment.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Inside a narrow dock office, fluorescent tube buzzing, a clipboard under a plastic cover labeled EAST TRANSPORT MANIFEST, water beading the window glass, a beige dot-matrix printer below the radio desk."}, "The dock office was a narrow room with a radio desk, two rain jackets on hooks, a corkboard with three notices and a faded postcard, and a clipboard under a plastic cover. The clipboard said EAST TRANSPORT MANIFEST. Every name had a mark beside it. Security. Maintenance. Animal containment. Food service. The names were typewritten, single-spaced, with one ruled column for the badge number and another for the pencil check, and at the bottom of the page, under the heading TEMPORARY CONTRACTORS, three printed names carried three pencil checks.", "Mateo Valverde was not there.", "He checked twice because paper sometimes lied badly.", "This paper lied cleanly.", "The lie was clean because nothing on the page was wrong. The page said the boat had left with the men whose names were on the page. The men whose names were on the page were on the boat. The page did not lie about anyone who was on the page. The page only lied about who was on the island. Mateo Valverde understood that the lie of paper was always the lie of what the paper had been told about, and that no paper had been told about him for some hours now.", "He picked up the radio handset.", "\"East transport, this is Mateo Valverde. Sanitation. I missed the vessel.\"", "The radio clicked.", "\"East transport, do you copy?\"", "Rain hit the roof. The loose sheet metal kept answering from outside.", "He set the handset down. He picked it up again. He pressed the button slower this time, the way men pressed buttons when they had begun to suspect that the button was no longer connected.", "\"Rosa? It is Mateo. The temporary.\"", "Nothing.", "A printer under the desk woke up.", "It was not a modern printer. Beige box. Fanfold paper. Black tractor holes. It made a dry insect noise and dragged one line into the world.", "ACCESS EVENT: BROWN, JOPHERY LOCATION: EAST DOCK OFFICE STATUS: ACTIVE", "Mateo Valverde tore the paper off.", "\"No,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "The printer gave him another line.", "ACTIVE PERSONNEL COUNT UPDATED.", "He looked through the office window at the empty dock.", "The park had counted a dead man and still had no place to put Mateo Valverde.", "He searched the drawers. A flare kit with two flares missing. A plastic poncho folded by a man who had folded it the same way many times. A half roll of duct tape with the cardboard core crushed flat. A grease pencil with a chewed end. A packet of crackers sealed in foil, the foil from a brand that had not been sold in Costa Rica since the year before. A small pocket New Testament in English with a name written inside the cover that was not Jophery Brown's. A nail clipper. A photograph paper-clipped to the back of the drawer of a shore in Florida, three children, a small dog. A folded square of toilet paper with two pills inside it. He did not know what the pills were. He kept them.", "He took everything except the drawer itself.", "He took the things the way a man took things on a sinking deck — quickly, without looking at faces, with the apology that is not an apology because the thing has already been done and the apology can come later if there is a later.", "The route sheet from Jophery Brown's locker had a corner map of the dock service road. Jophery Brown had drawn arrows around the main gate and written:", "IF DOCK CLOSED, BACK THROUGH PUMP HOUSE.", "Mateo Valverde did not want the pump house.", "The pump house was inland. Inland meant fences. Fences meant animals. Animals meant the men with rifles had not stayed where Mateo Valverde needed them.", "He went anyway.", "He went because there was nothing else to do, and because Jophery Brown had drawn the arrow, and because a man whose locker had been searched and whose badge had been taken and whose name was now traveling on a printer in his place had earned the right to be obeyed about a small map.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "Concrete ramp under a pump house door, two blue chemical drums strapped under a wet tarp, a service road badge reader glowing in the dark behind chain-link, rain sheeting from the awning."}, "The pump house door stood ten meters past the dock office, half hidden by two blue drums strapped under a tarp. The drums had a small spider's web between them that the rain had filled with water and not yet broken. Water ran down the little concrete ramp leading to the door. Mateo Valverde tried his own badge first.", "He had to know.", "Red.", "Jophery Brown's badge gave green.", "Inside, the air smelled of hot motors and old salt. Pumps thudded below the floor, moving water through pipes Mateo Valverde had never seen on a visitor map. A wall panel showed dock sump levels in red needles. Two needles sat in the yellow. One was buried in the red. The needle in the red did not move when Mateo Valverde watched it. It had been buried for a while. It had been buried while the men with rifles had been busy doing other things.", "On the far wall, a second reader blinked beside a door marked SERVICE ROAD B.", "Mateo Valverde crossed to it.", "The pump under his boots stopped.", "Not slowed. Not coughed.", "Stopped.", "Every pipe in the room clicked once as pressure changed. The clicks ran along the wall in the order the pipes were going to remember the change in. After the clicks, there was a quiet that was not quiet. It was the quiet of a building that had stopped a thing without warning, and was now listening to find out what would happen next.", "Mateo Valverde did not move.", "The reader by the service road went green before he touched it.", "From the dark space beyond the door, something breathed through its nose.", "Once.", "Slowly.", "The breath was not the breath of a man.", "The breath was the breath of a thing that had been quiet for as long as the pumps had been loud, and was not quiet anymore."]},
  13: {"n": 13, "title": "Chapter 13: The Last Shuttle", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A worker crouched on a wet pump house roof in heavy rain, gravel under his palms, an abandoned yellow shuttle bus at an angle on a service road below, one headlight pointed at the trees."}, "The breath came from low down.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} did not move his feet. Moving feet made rubber squeak on wet concrete. He had learned that in the {{raptor}} bay. Everything loud began as something small a worker forgot to respect.", "The door had opened only a handspan. Through the gap he saw rain, black leaves, and a pale shape near the ramp. It was not a raptor. Too low. Too round through the shoulder. It sniffed again and pushed its nose against the bottom of the door.", "Mateo Valverde saw small teeth.", "Not small enough.", "The animal was the size of a goat. The teeth were the teeth of a thing that had been told all its life that it ate other things. Its eyes had a faint yellow ring of the kind a person did not put in eyes when designing a pet.", "He backed up one step. The pump room gave him a stupid gift. The stopped motor restarted. The floor jumped under him. The animal outside flinched away from the door and made a sound like a dog warned off a kitchen.", "Mateo Valverde hit the close button.", "Nothing happened.", "Of course.", "He used the grease pencil from the dock office and marked the door with one word.", "NO.", "Then he took the maintenance ladder.", "The ladder went up to a roof hatch and out into rain so hard it seemed personal. Mateo Valverde crawled, dragged the hatch shut, and lay flat on the gravel roof while the small animal below worried at the door gap. He kept the flare kit under his chest. He kept {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge in his fist. The fist was so wet he could feel the ridges of the laminate against his palm.", "When he lifted his head, he saw the last shuttle.", "It sat on the service road fifty meters inland, angled across the yellow line with one headlight pointing at the trees and one at the sky. The driver's door hung open. Its hazard lights blinked without rhythm, as if one bulb had to think before it remembered.", "Mateo Valverde climbed down the far side of the pump house and ran crouched along the concrete drainage lip. The drainage lip was four inches wide. The drainage lip was the only thing between him and a stretch of grass he did not want to be standing in.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Interior of an abandoned tour shuttle at night, the driver's door hanging open, a clipboard on the dashboard, the green-glow radio handset in a worker's hand, rainwater pooling on rubber floor mats."}, "The shuttle smelled of wet vinyl, diesel, and fear.", "Fear had a smell, {{Tomás Araya}} had told him once at the canteen. It was not the smell people thought it was. It was the smell of clothing that had been clean an hour earlier.", "No driver.", "No passengers.", "The key was still in the ignition.", "Mateo Valverde laughed once, because his body was stupid and thought that meant luck.", "He turned the key.", "The engine coughed, caught for two seconds, and died.", "He tried again.", "The engine clicked.", "The fuel gauge lay flat under E.", "Someone had left the shuttle with the lights on and the engine running until it had drunk itself empty. The clipboard beside the driver's seat had a printed route. EAST DOCK - VISITOR CENTER - HELIPAD SUPPORT. Under it, in pencil:", "NOT FOR TEMP STAFF.", "Mateo Valverde stared at the words until rainwater from his hair dropped onto the ink and made the T in TEMP blur. The blur made it the same word for everyone. He left it that way.", "The shuttle radio still had power.", "He pressed the handset. \"Anyone on transport channel, this is sanitation. I have a disabled shuttle on east service road.\"", "Static.", "Then a child's voice, far away and thin.", "\"Hello?\"", "Mateo Valverde froze.", "He knew that voice was not talking to him. It came through the wrong channel, bent by water and failing repeaters. It was young. It tried not to sound young.", "\"Hello? Lex, don't touch—\"", "A boy's voice cut through, faster, higher.", "\"It's pulling, it's pulling the cable—\"", "The girl again. \"Shut up, shut up, please.\"", "Then a man's voice. Far. One word, shouted, the rest cut.", "\"—down—\"", "Something heavy hit metal. Not gunshot. Not engine. Weight against a frame. The sound a body made against the side of something built to hold its shape. The radio carrier held the noise long enough for Mateo Valverde to count two of his own heartbeats inside it.", "A new sound came under it. An alarm. Two tones. The kind that meant a door was open that should not be.", "Mateo Valverde reached for the transmit button.", "His thumb stopped above the red plastic.", "If he answered, what name would the system send?", "Mateo Valverde did not exist.", "Jophery Brown was active at East Dock.", "The radio display blinked, searched, and found a label.", "CALLER ID: BROWN, J.", "His thumb went cold against the plastic. The girl was waiting on the other end with a brother who was four or five and a man who had stopped shouting. If he keyed the mic, a dead man's name would arrive in their speaker. He did not know if a child could hold that on top of whatever was eating their roof.", "He did not know if he could.", "He took his thumb off the button.", "The girl's voice came back. Closer. A strange clean closeness, the kind that meant a repeater had finally caught.", "\"Is someone there?\"", "His chest pulled in once, hard, without his permission. He set the handset down on the seat as if it might break, the way a man set down a thing that had a child's voice still on it.", "Outside the shuttle, something heavy stepped into the water behind him."]},
  14: {"n": 14, "title": "Chapter 14: Return to Sender", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Under a tour shuttle bench at night, a worker's hands gripping a wrench, a thick gray dinosaur tongue touching the steering wheel, foil cracker wrapper on the floor."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} slid under the shuttle bench.", "It was not bravery. It was not a plan. It was the only place his body found before the step outside became two steps, then three, then the wet sound of something large smelling the open driver's door.", "The bench frame pressed into his ribs. A wrench rolled against his knee. He caught it before it could hit the floor.", "The thing outside put its head into the shuttle.", "Mateo Valverde saw a gray tongue touch the steering wheel.", "Not the tyrannosaur. Not a {{raptor}}. Bigger than the small animal at the pump house, with a heavy snout and eyes set where a cow's eyes might have been if cows had been built from bad decisions. The eyes did not move together. One looked at the steering wheel. The other looked at the rain. The eyes were not coordinated because the animal had not yet been required to coordinate them, and Mateo Valverde was a man inside a shape the animal had not been told yet how to read.", "It huffed once and took the crackers from the seat with the wrapper still on.", "Mateo Valverde held the wrench with both hands.", "The animal chewed foil.", "The radio said, \"Hello?\"", "The animal lifted its head.", "Mateo Valverde let go of the wrench and grabbed the radio cord. He pulled the handset under the bench and pressed the side button against his chest to muffle it.", "\"Do not answer this channel,\" he whispered. \"Go quiet.\"", "Static.", "He did not know if the girl heard him. He did not know if the girl had a hand free for the radio anymore. He did not know if his whisper had been loud enough to leave the shuttle.", "The animal outside swallowed the crackers and left.", "It left the way an animal left a place that had given up the only interesting thing about it. A sniff. A turn. A wet step. Then nothing. Then a slow distant splash from the direction of the drainage lip.", "Mateo Valverde stayed under the bench until his legs shook from staying still.", "When he crawled out, the radio display had changed.", "TRANSMISSION ROUTED BROWN, J. / SERVICE MAINTENANCE", "Below that:", "RETURN TO SENDER", "He took the shuttle's maintenance clipboard and the dead radio handset. The handset had a screw-on plug. Anything with a screw-on plug could be useful if a person was desperate enough.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A weathered communications cabinet under a tin rain shelter beside a service road, three padlocks of different ages, the bottom one already broken, a worker prying it open with a wrench."}, "The nearest communications cabinet was marked on {{Jophery Brown}}'s route sheet as COM-3. It sat under a tin rain shelter beside the service road, between two trees that had grown too close to the concrete. The cabinet had three locks. Jophery Brown's badge opened the top lock. The middle lock needed a key. The bottom lock had been broken before Mateo Valverde was hired.", "He opened it with the wrench.", "Inside were phone junctions, paper tags, dust turned to paste, and a laminated service ticket sealed in a plastic sleeve.", "Jophery Brown had signed the ticket.", "READER D-17 MISREPORTS USER ID AFTER LOCAL FALLBACK. POSSIBLE BACKUP TABLE CORRUPTION. REQUEST: DO NOT CLOSE UNTIL TESTED.", "At the bottom, in a different hand:", "CLOSED - NO ISSUE FOUND.", "Mateo Valverde read it.", "He read it again.", "Not because it was complicated.", "Because it was simple.", "Jophery Brown had seen it. Before the storm. Before Nedry. Before Mateo Valverde ever signed a contract. The park had been practicing how to forget people and call the forgetting fixed.", "The \"different hand\" at the bottom was the kind of handwriting a manager used when he had decided what the answer to a question was going to be before the question had been asked.", "Mateo Valverde used the grease pencil to write on the inside of the cabinet door.", "MATEO VALVERDE ALIVE EAST SERVICE ROAD TEMP SANITATION", "He added the time from his watch.", "He wrote it the way Jophery Brown had written J. BROWN on the strip of tape inside locker 18, neat and square, on the small stupid hope that some other person on this island in some next week would open this cabinet and read his name and decide that the name was a fact and not a ticket.", "Then he tried the cabinet phone.", "The line clicked through three empty rooms and one busy signal. A woman finally answered.", "\"Maintenance dispatch.\"", "Mateo Valverde almost dropped the handset.", "\"This is Mateo Valverde. Temporary contractor. I am still on the island.\"", "Silence.", "\"Say again?\"", "\"Mateo Valverde. Sanitation. I missed evacuation. The access system has erased my badge.\"", "More silence. Paper moved near the receiver. Somewhere on her side of the line a small radio played a station that was not playing news. The station was playing a song from a year ago, in English, the kind of song people had forgotten by the time it stopped being on the radio.", "\"This ticket is already closed,\" the woman said.", "\"What ticket?\"", "\"D-17 user mismatch. Brown, Jophery. Closed no issue found.\"", "\"No. Listen to me. I am not—\"", "The line cut to a tone.", "The cabinet printer stamped one new status onto the old ticket.", "COMPLETED.", "Mateo Valverde stood with the wrench in one hand and the dead receiver in the other. The rain on the tin roof above him had a steady metallic note. He listened to it for the length of time a man listened to a sound when he had not yet decided what to do with the next minute. The note did not change. The rain did not become more polite. The cabinet did not retract the stamp.", "He hung up the receiver carefully, as if it had been borrowed.", "He left the cabinet door open.", "The grease-pencil words on the inside of the door faced the rain.", "He hoped that was enough."]},
  15: {"n": 15, "title": "Chapter 15: The Park Remembers the Dead", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A dim staff break room behind a maintenance office, a corkboard crowded with worker photos, a soda machine without power, plastic chairs around a Formica table, fluorescent tube flickering above."}, "The staff break room was behind the maintenance office, past a soda machine with no power and a door that opened for {{Jophery Brown}} without asking {{Mateo Valverde}} anything.", "Mateo Valverde went in because his hands would not stop shaking.", "He told himself he was looking for batteries.", "That was mostly true.", "The break room had a microwave, six plastic chairs, a sink full of mugs, a board of safety notices, and a cork strip crowded with photographs. Men on boats. Women holding babies. A boy in a school uniform with two front teeth missing. A wedding picture folded at the corner. A Polaroid of {{Tomás Araya}} standing beside a service cart with both thumbs up, pretending the cart was a race car.", "Mateo Valverde took the Polaroid down and put it in his shirt pocket.", "Not for a reason he could name.", "Or for a reason he could name and did not want to. Tomás Araya had stayed on the dirty side of a door an hour earlier. Tomás Araya had said <i>I have one more room</i>. Tomás Araya was a man who folded his sleeves twice with tape, and a man who folded his sleeves twice with tape was not the kind of man who left a service bay before he was ready, and a man who was not ready was the kind of man who was still in the service bay when the network dropped.", "Jophery Brown had three photographs.", "The first showed him in a baseball cap, holding a fish. The fish was small. Jophery Brown was proud anyway. He held it the way a man held something that took longer than it should have. Mateo Valverde had cleaned that kind of pride off the floor of every break room he had ever worked. Men brought fish too small to feed anyone. Other men teased them. Then everyone went back to work, fed.", "The second photograph was a kitchen table. A woman sat on the left. Two girls sat in front of her. The youngest girl had birthday cake on her chin, a clean white smear under her bottom lip, eyes already laughing at whoever had pointed the camera. The older girl held a plastic fork like she was about to make a point with it.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the cake on the youngest girl's chin until his throat hurt.", "He moved to the third.", "The third photograph was the {{raptor}} service awning. Four men in coveralls. Jophery Brown on the left, taller than the others, one hand on a wire fence post. Someone had written along the white border, in a careless slant.", "FIVE MINUTES, BROWN SAID.", "Mateo Valverde did not laugh.", "He understood the joke.", "Jophery Brown had said five minutes was enough time to get safe, in a place where five minutes was not enough time to get safe. The men around him had laughed when he was alive. Then he had been wrong by a margin no one wanted to measure. Now they kept the photograph because grief found a way to wear a uniform.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A Formica desk with a worker's open cubby below a corkboard, a folded complaint form, a clean pair of socks, two pay stubs, a worker's hand reading careful printed handwriting."}, "He searched Jophery Brown's cubby below the corkboard. Batteries. A clean pair of socks. A pack of gum. Two pay stubs. A folded complaint form.", "The complaint form was dated six days before Jophery Brown died.", "It said reader D-17 had opened for the wrong person during a drill. It said the fallback table was older than the live roster. It said temporary and transfer personnel were not being tested under degrade conditions. It said, in Jophery Brown's careful print:", "IF THIS FAILS DURING A CONTAINMENT EVENT, SOMEONE WILL BE LOCKED WHERE THEY SHOULD NOT BE.", "Dale Haskins had signed the bottom.", "ACKNOWLEDGED.", "No action line.", "No repair line.", "Acknowledged was a word people used when they wanted a problem to die on paper. <i>Acknowledged</i> was the word a manager wrote when he wanted to mean <i>I have read this and I am not going to spend money on it</i>. <i>Acknowledged</i> was a word that did not require any next word.", "Mateo Valverde put the complaint form with the manifest and the printed access log. Evidence was too strong a word. Evidence belonged to people who could stand in a room and be believed.", "He had paper.", "Paper got wet.", "The emergency light over the door blinked twice and turned steady red.", "The PA came alive.", "A woman read the same line in English and Spanish. ALL PERSONNEL TO NEAREST SECURE ROOM. Her voice was prerecorded. The pause between languages was always the same length, even now.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the secure-room sign on the wall. A green arrow. A diagram of a room with one door and no windows.", "He took Jophery Brown's route sheet out of his back pocket.", "Jophery Brown had drawn the same room. Same shape. Same arrow. In the margin, in the same careful print as the complaint form:", "NO WINDOWS. ONE READER. BAD HINGE.", "One worker, talking to another worker. A man who had walked the corridors enough times to know which doors lied. A man who had written the bad-hinge note before the storm, before Nedry, before Mateo Valverde was on a manifest.", "If the reader chose Jophery Brown, the door opened.", "If the reader chose Mateo Valverde, the door did not.", "If the reader chose nothing, the bad hinge stayed where it had always been, and a man on the inside of the room would be the kind of man who waited for someone outside to remember him.", "He put the sheet back in his pocket and went the other way.", "In the hallway, the access panel showed a list of recent entries.", "BROWN, JOPHERY - EAST DOCK OFFICE BROWN, JOPHERY - PUMP HOUSE BROWN, JOPHERY - SHUTTLE 4 BROWN, JOPHERY - COM-3 BROWN, JOPHERY - STAFF BREAK ROOM", "The cursor blinked.", "Then it added one more line.", "BROWN, JOPHERY - RAPTOR SERVICE ENTRY", "Mateo Valverde was not at raptor service.", "He looked at the badge in his hand. The plastic was warm from his palm. The clip was bent the way it had been when he had pulled it out of the drain, and the lanyard hole was still torn in the same way, and the photograph on the laminate was still Jophery Brown in fluorescent light.", "Somebody else had Jophery Brown's name on a different reader, in a different room, six minutes ago.", "Mateo Valverde closed his hand around the badge.", "He went the other way."]},
  16: {"n": 16, "title": "Chapter 16: Rex Weather", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A flooded maintenance tunnel under a culvert, brown water rising over a worker's boots, fluorescent bulbs failing in groups, a length of chain with a metal clip drifting past in the current."}, "The safest route on {{Jophery Brown}}'s sheet ran toward the sound.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} did not know what made the sound. Not at first. The building did not shake like a movie building. It shifted in small dishonest ways. Dust came down from pipe clamps. Water rings trembled in a coffee cup on a maintenance desk. Somewhere above him, metal bent with a long groan and then stopped.", "The men in the {{raptor}} yard had talked about the tyrannosaur the way people talked about a storm.", "Keep your distance.", "Watch the fences.", "Don't assume because it is far away that it is not coming.", "Rex weather, one of them had said, and the others laughed because men laughed when a phrase was good enough to hide behind.", "Mateo Valverde understood it now.", "The phrase was a way to say a thing so the thing did not require a man to look at it.", "The tour road maintenance tunnel ran beneath a culvert and came up behind generator shed C. It was supposed to be dry except during seasonal service. It was not dry. Brown water moved against Mateo Valverde's ankles and carried leaves, insulation, and one length of chain with a metal clip at the end.", "The chain had hair caught in it.", "Goat hair.", "The hair was short and black. The clip was the kind of clip that fastened to a leg cuff or a halter. The chain had been used at the raptor yard for what raptor handlers called <i>positioning</i>, which was a word raptor handlers used because they did not want to use the word <i>bait</i>.", "Mateo Valverde stepped over it and did not look up at the ceiling.", "Looking up would not help.", "He followed the tunnel by touch. The lights failed in groups. Three bulbs on, two bulbs dead, one bulb buzzing like a trapped fly. Jophery Brown's route sheet said the tunnel door at the far end opened with permanent staff access during local safe mode.", "It did.", "Green.", "Green lied less underground. The doors were older. They expected less from people.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Inside a half-flooded generator shed at night, a wall cracked near the floor, a glimpse of a downed fence and a yellow tour vehicle through the gap, a maintenance vest with reflective stripes hanging on a hook."}, "Generator shed C was half flooded. The outside wall had cracked near the floor. Through the crack Mateo Valverde saw a section of fence lying flat in mud and rain. Beyond it, the tour road disappeared into trees. One of the yellow tour vehicles sat sideways across the lane with its roof crushed down at the back.", "The goat chain ended under it.", "Mateo Valverde found two dry road flares in a cabinet, a coil of rope, and a maintenance vest with reflective stripes. He put the vest on because he wanted to be seen by people and not seen by animals, and the island did not allow both wishes at once.", "The shed radio was mounted to the wall. He tried it because he hated himself if he did not try.", "\"This is Mateo Valverde. Generator shed C. I am alive.\"", "The radio answered with a man's breathing.", "The breathing was the breathing of a man who had been about to say a different thing and had decided, in the half-second between Mateo Valverde's words, to say nothing yet.", "Then: \"Identify.\"", "Mateo Valverde closed his eyes.", "\"Mateo Valverde. Temporary sanitation.\"", "\"That name is not on my board.\"", "\"I know.\"", "\"Who are you with?\"", "\"No one.\"", "\"How did you access C shed?\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at Jophery Brown's badge in his hand.", "\"Permanent staff badge.\"", "The man swore softly. The swearing was practiced, the way a man swore who had been trained not to swear and was using the training in reverse to keep his voice level.", "\"Brown?\"", "\"No.\"", "\"Brown is dead.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Then who the hell is using his badge?\"", "\"I am.\"", "The radio went quiet for two breaths.", "Mateo Valverde pressed the button before the man could swear again.", "\"My badge is in the system as deleted. The fallback table has Brown active. I am not pretending to be him. I needed a door.\"", "The man on the radio took a breath through his teeth.", "\"Okay,\" he said. \"Okay. Stay where you are. Stay there. I'm sending—\"", "Before Mateo Valverde could ask what the man was sending, the outside fence wire jumped.", "Not from electricity.", "From weight.", "Something moved on the tour road. He saw only one foot in the mud, three toes spreading under the rain, each claw pressing a black crescent into the service lane. The foot was not the foot of a thing he had drawn on his map. The foot was the foot of a thing whose paddock was on the other side of the island.", "The radio man said, \"Do not move.\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at the door behind him.", "The reader light went out."]},
  17: {"n": 17, "title": "Chapter 17: Utility Level B", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A service hatch in a concrete shed floor, two recessed bolts loosened with a wrench, hot air rising from below into a dim utility tunnel"}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} got out through the floor.", "That was not a thing the safety signs admitted a person could do. The safety signs preferred stairs, muster points, and calm walking. The shed floor had a service hatch with two recessed bolts and a warning about confined spaces. The bolts were not tight. Nothing on the island was tight if a worker had needed to open it often enough.", "He used the wrench from the shuttle.", "Above him, the animal on the tour road breathed against the cracked wall. The breath had pressure to it. The cracked wall had begun to make a noise it had not made before, a long thin shaving sound where the concrete had decided to tell its rebar what was happening.", "Mateo Valverde took his time on the second bolt. Hurrying stripped bolts. Stripped bolts made noise. Noise made teeth.", "The hatch opened into hot air.", "He climbed down a ladder into Utility Level B and pulled the hatch after him with one hand. The dark below smelled of old batteries, mineral water, and the green-black odor of drains that had been asked to do too much.", "He stood at the bottom of the ladder and listened to the building.", "A pipe overhead ticked with hot water. Another beside it ran cold and silent. The cold one was dead. He put his palm to it and confirmed. Pump house upstream had cut out, or someone had closed a valve. The hot one was still on the boiler loop. Boilers ran on their own logic for a long time after the men left.", "A floor channel pulled water past his boot in a thin pulse. Something somewhere was still washing.", "The cable trays hummed. Not all of them. Two of three. He counted as he walked. Lighting circuit live. Communication trunk live. Auxiliary tray dead. The park was not dark yet. The park was choosing what to keep on.", "Mateo Valverde read the systems the way another man read a face.", "He had read systems his whole working life. The hospital's vacuum line that gurgled when surgery was in session. The bar's beer compressor that thunked when a keg was running low. The harbor's ice plant that had a different tone for each of its two compressors and told a man who knew how to listen which compressor was about to need work. A building told you what it was doing if you stayed quiet long enough to hear it.", "This building was telling him three things.", "It was telling him the boilers were on.", "It was telling him the pumps were off.", "It was telling him the network had not yet decided whether the lights mattered.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A long concrete service corridor with overhead pipe runs, cable trays, and laminated instruction plates, one bare bulb every twenty feet"}, "Utility Level B was not a level.", "It was a mistake repeated under different buildings until someone gave it a name.", "Concrete corridors. Pipe runs. Cable trays. Floor channels. Little rooms with pumps, switches, and laminated instructions written for men who already knew what they were looking at. Mateo Valverde had cleaned hospitals older than this park. Hospitals hid their important work in back corridors too. Oxygen. Waste. Laundry. Bodies. The front of a place could lie only because the back kept working.", "He walked the spine for a hundred feet before he found the schematic.", "It was bolted to the wall under yellowed plastic. Someone had drawn over the original lines in red grease pencil. Someone else had drawn over the red lines in blue. The corrections went two layers deep before anyone gave up. Two layers of correction was the depth at which a building had decided that its own map was a thing the next worker would have to learn from a man with a wrench, not from the map.", "SERVICE SPINE B VISITOR CENTER / KITCHEN / CONTROL SUPPORT / NORTH MAINTENANCE", "Visitor center.", "Mateo Valverde touched the word with two wet fingers.", "If any rescue remained, it would go there. If any radio still reached the mainland, it would be near control. If the children on the wrong channel were real, the visitor center was where a child would run when adults told them a building was safe.", "He copied the schematic onto the back of the transport manifest with the grease pencil. The lines came out fat and ugly. Good. Pretty maps were for guests.", "Halfway down the spine, the lights changed color.", "Not off.", "Blue.", "The blue lights marked animal quarantine support. Mateo Valverde knew that from {{Tomás Araya}}, who had said blue meant <i>do not bring guest laundry through unless you wanted to sign more paper than your grandchildren could read</i>.", "A manual valve wheel stood beside a door marked AIR HANDLER B-4. Someone had tied a strip of blue cloth around the wheel.", "The same blue as the fabric from the {{raptor}} drain.", "Mateo Valverde stopped.", "He looked at the strip. The cloth was the same weave. The same dye. The same machine-thread along the seam, white where the dye had not taken. A man had tied a piece of cloth to a valve wheel as a marker, and that piece of cloth had come from the same uniform as the strip Tomás Araya had told him to bag and not look at.", "A man had marked the valve himself.", "A man.", "Singular.", "Inside the building, after the rollback.", "The route sheet had a note near B-4:", "SHORTCUT IF DRY. NEVER IF WET.", "The floor was wet.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-3.webp", "alt": "A badge reader beside a steel door marked AIR HANDLER B-4 glowing green over an open palm in a corridor lit by cold blue safety bulbs"}, "Behind him, somewhere up the ladder shaft, metal screamed as the service hatch tore open. The scream was the scream of metal that had been pulled in a direction the metal had not been engineered to be pulled. The bolts had not stripped. The hinges had given up first.", "Mateo Valverde put {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge to B-4.", "Red.", "He put his own temporary badge to it because panic made people stupid.", "The reader thought longer than the others.", "Then it turned green.", "For the first time since the locker hallway, Mateo Valverde got a green light.", "He stood with his hand still on the reader. The green washed across his palm and the back of his wrist and the cuff of his shirt. The park knew his face. Under his own name. The system that had ignored him for two days now welcomed him by his payroll number into a corridor with quarantine cloth on the valve wheel and water on the floor.", "The reader had not been told yet that he was not real.", "Or had been told and had forgotten, in the way buildings forgot things at three in the morning when half their memory had been put to sleep.", "A small laugh moved in his chest and stopped before it reached his teeth.", "Up the spine, something heavy dropped from the ladder shaft and landed on concrete.", "Mateo Valverde went through B-4."]},
  18: {"n": 18, "title": "Chapter 18: Kitchen Light", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Service-side visitor center kitchen with stainless prep counters, swinging double doors, a fallen pan rack, and emergency bulbs reflected in puddled water across the tile."}, "The door opened because a forgotten reader remembered him.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} stood with his hand on the badge. He watched the green light. He waited for it to change.", "It did not.", "AIR HANDLER B-4 was loud, hot, narrow. The floor was wet under the fan housings. Wet was wrong. Dry meant no condensation spill. Dry meant no stormwater backflow. Dry meant no animal washdown pushing the wrong direction through the service spine.", "The shortcut was wet.", "Mateo Valverde went through anyway.", "He had stopped believing in good routes. He had routes that existed.", "The air handler put him behind the kitchen. He knew it before the sign. The smell told him. Cold meat. Lemon cleaner. Fryer oil gone stale. Something sweet left too long under glass. The smell of a kitchen that had been cleaning itself for an evening service that had not happened, while the staff had walked out to a shuttle without finishing the dishwashing rack.", "The kitchen lights were on.", "That was wrong enough to make him crouch.", "A safe building did not need every light. A building pretending to be safe did. A kitchen with full overhead at this hour meant either the staff had been told to leave the lights on for an inspection that was no longer coming, or the system had decided this room was a guest room now, and was performing for guests who were no longer there.", "He opened the service panel and stepped into the back corridor behind the freezers. Stainless steel broke the emergency bulbs into stripes. A rack of clean pans had fallen across the floor. One pan rocked. Slow. Small. Nothing had touched it. The compressor under the floor kept kicking on and off, the way a compressor kicked when its thermostat had been told to keep working but its supply line had not been told to give it any cold.", "Mateo Valverde listened.", "No voices. No radio. No men pretending.", "He moved through the prep area with one hand on the counter. Flour stuck to the water on his sleeve. Of all the things the island had put on him, flour was the most normal. He laughed once, very small, the way a man laughed at a thing that was the most normal thing because the thing reminded him that other rooms in other places did normal things at this hour.", "There were prints on the floor.", "Small shoes.", "Two sets.", "Running.", "The smaller set had come in first. The larger set had come in after, and had stopped near the prep table, and had turned, and had crossed back, and had then turned a second time toward the kitchen doors. The smaller set had been faster. The smaller set had been the one running.", "The prints in the flour were sharper than the prints on the wet tile, but the prints on the wet tile had gone to the swinging doors.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the prints. He looked at the swinging kitchen doors. He looked at {{Jophery Brown}}'s sheet. Service route first. Guest route last. The park killed workers in the spaces between.", "He did not follow them into the dining room.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Two sets of small muddy shoe prints crossing wet kitchen tile beside a fallen ladle and a streak of flour, lit by a single emergency bulb under stainless prep counters."}, "He found a chef's jacket and wrapped it around his left forearm. Not armor. Cloth. Cloth was better than skin. The chef's jacket had a name embroidered above the breast pocket. The name was not a name Mateo Valverde knew, and not a name he was about to find a man for, but a name was on the jacket and that meant the man had been here, in this kitchen, in the part of the day that had been a workday, and had hung the jacket on a hook above the apron station, and had not taken it down before the shuttle.", "In dry storage he took canned pineapple, a box cutter, and a rolling cart. The cart had a bad left wheel that pulled. He took it anyway. Carts belonged to him more than guns did.", "The freezer alarm began to beep.", "One beep every two seconds. Door open.", "Mateo Valverde turned toward the freezer aisle.", "The walk-in stood open three inches. Cold fog rolled out at floor level, the slow heavy kind of fog that came out of a freezer when the freezer's air had been displacing the warmer air of the corridor for a while. Three inches of door was enough for a child. Three inches of door was enough for other things too.", "Something inside scraped once against metal shelving.", "He backed away.", "The cart wheel squealed.", "The scraping stopped.", "Mateo Valverde crouched and grabbed the wheel with one hand to kill it. The cart twisted under his grip. A can fell from the lower shelf and hit the tile.", "The freezer door moved.", "Not much.", "Just enough.", "In the polished metal of the opposite counter, he saw the reflection.", "A long head.", "Lifting in the cold.", "The head had been low. The head had been below the height of the bottom shelf. The head was not low anymore. It was not the head of a thing that had walked in by mistake. It was the head of a thing that had been waiting for a sound from the direction of the cart, and had decided that the sound had been worth interrupting whatever it had been doing inside the freezer for.", "Mateo Valverde did not turn around.", "A man who turned around to confirm a reflection was a man who had given up his half-second.", "He held the box cutter against his thigh, low, where the reflection would not see it. He kept his eyes on the polished steel. He waited for the head to move again, and for the body behind the head to make the small forward motion that a thing made when it had decided to come into a room.", "The head tilted.", "The head listened.", "The freezer fog crawled along the floor.", "Outside, far off, on the far side of the visitor center, a child screamed.", "The head stopped listening to the kitchen.", "It listened to the scream.", "Then, very slowly, it pulled back into the freezer."]},
  19: {"n": 19, "title": "Chapter 19: Not My Rescue", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A back-of-house visitor center corridor split between guest stairs rising on the right and a staff service door on the left, wet boot prints crossing in opposite directions under a single emergency bulb."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} did not run toward the guest stairs.", "He hated that later.", "At the time, he saw three things. The freezer reflection. The service door two meters behind him. A white towel hanging off the cart handle. He pulled the towel loose, threw it at the freezer alarm panel, and hit the service door with his shoulder before the animal in the cold decided the beeping meant food.", "The guest stairs were on his right.", "Voices came from that direction.", "A girl. A boy. A man shouting one word Mateo Valverde could not make out.", "He had one second to turn.", "He stopped instead.", "He put his hand flat against the wall and listened.", "The wall was cold under his palm. The voices bent. He could not tell if they were moving up the stairs or coming down them. The stairwell threw the sound. Carpet on the guest side ate the footsteps. He had walked the service spine of this building. He had never walked the guest stairs. He did not know which landing the voices were on. He did not know whether the man with the one word was above the children or below them. He did not know whether the children were the children from the radio, the ones who had said <i>Lex don't touch</i> and <i>it's pulling</i>, or whether they were a second pair he had not heard about. He did not know whether the man was their man.", "He did not know his geometry in the wrong half of the building.", "His feet were on tile. The voices were on carpet. Between him and them was a wall he could not see through. A guest stair he did not know the turns of. A landing that might be empty by the time he climbed it.", "The service door behind him was already closing.", "Green did not mean open.", "Open did not mean enough time.", "Mateo Valverde moved.", "He did not move toward the stairs.", "The corridor beyond the kitchen ran past staff toilets and a janitor closet. Mateo Valverde stopped with his forehead against the painted block wall. He could still hear the freezer alarm through the door. Then the alarm cut off.", "Something hit the kitchen side of the door.", "He kept moving.", "He told himself the children had adults. The guest stairs led upward. His route led to radios. One more body in the kitchen would not make the children safer.", "All those things might have been true.", "They did not help.", "The thing they did not help with was a small thing his chest did, just under the breastbone, when he kept walking. Mateo Valverde did not have a word for it. He was not going to find one walking. Some things had no word in any language he had ever tried.", "At the janitor closet, someone groaned.", "Mateo Valverde opened the door with the box cutter in his hand.", "Rosa was inside.", "He knew her voice first. The woman from the radio. East transport. Her hair was plastered against her face. One trouser leg was black with blood below the knee. She held a mop handle like a spear and almost put it through his chest before she saw him.", "\"You,\" Rosa said.", "\"Me.\"", "\"You missed it.\"", "\"I noticed.\"", "Rosa gave one breath that was almost a laugh and bent forward until her forehead touched the mop handle.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Rosa braced inside a janitor closet with bleach jugs and a yellow bucket behind her, mop handle lowered, blood blackening her left trouser leg, while Mateo crouches with a chef's jacket in one hand."}, "She had stayed for a driver who never reached the dock.", "She told him in pieces. The driver had been a kitchen man named Ortega, on his second island contract, who had run back from the dock to fetch his daughter's medical paper from a locker because he had been told he could not return for it later. The locker had been on the contractor side of the visitor center, fifteen minutes round trip in good weather, twenty-five in bad. Ortega had not come back. A gate had stuck. A tire on the second shuttle had blown. The radio had told Rosa to shelter. The shelter door had locked on the wrong side. Every part of her story had an instruction in it. Every instruction had failed by five minutes.", "The leg was a deep cut from a metal bracket in the gate housing. Not from a tooth. Mateo Valverde did not say that out loud, because Rosa already knew, and saying it would have suggested he had checked.", "Mateo Valverde wrapped her leg with the chef's jacket. He tied it above the knee. He tied it again below.", "\"Can you walk?\"", "\"Badly.\"", "\"Badly is a kind of walking.\"", "\"You sound like my father.\"", "\"I am sorry.\"", "\"Don't be. He was a good man.\"", "They moved together down the service corridor. Rosa knew the visitor center better than Mateo Valverde knew it. Mateo Valverde knew the underside better than Rosa. Between them they had half a map and one working leg, and the kind of patience two strangers had for each other when each of them knew the other was the only person in the building who was going to keep them upright.", "At the end of the corridor, a stairwell sign pointed up to HELIPAD SUPPORT.", "Rosa saw it and touched his arm.", "\"If they come back, that is where.\"", "The stairwell door had a reader. No manual bar. Mateo Valverde put his temporary badge to it.", "Red.", "{{Jophery Brown}}'s badge.", "Green.", "The lock opened.", "\"Brown?\" Rosa said.", "\"It is the badge that works.\"", "\"Whose.\"", "\"His.\"", "She looked at him for a second longer than she needed to. The look did not say <i>you should not have it</i>. The look said <i>I have understood what you have done, and I am too tired tonight to decide whether it is the kind of thing I will think badly of you for tomorrow</i>.", "\"Move,\" Rosa said.", "Behind them, from the kitchen service door, came three soft taps.", "Not impacts.", "Claws, testing.", "The taps came in the rhythm of a thing that had decided which side of a door it preferred, and was checking with its hands which side that was.", "Mateo Valverde pulled Rosa through the stairwell door.", "The door closed behind them with the small click a forgotten reader gave when it had once been a building's handshake and was now its goodbye."]},
  20: {"n": 20, "title": "Chapter 20: Compy Work", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A trash sorting room behind the visitor center with red biohazard bags split open, white food bags torn at the seams, floor drain grates clogged with rind and gauze, small wet three-toed prints crossing the tile."}, "The little ones came through the trash room.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} heard them before he saw them. Not footsteps. Too light. Scratches. Plastic crackling. Wet snouts pushing into bags. The sound made the hair on his arms lift because it belonged to work, not monsters. Rats in hospital bins. Dogs behind markets. Animals that found what people threw away and made a living from it.", "Rosa leaned on the mop handle and whispered, \"What is that?\"", "\"Garbage.\"", "\"Garbage does not breathe.\"", "\"This garbage does.\"", "The helipad stairwell had taken them up one level and stopped at a smoke door with no power. No red. No green. No light. The manual handle had been removed for construction and not replaced. Someone had taped over the empty screw holes as if tape could become metal if a supervisor did not look closely.", "They had gone back down.", "A door on the lower landing took them through the back of a meeting room with a long wet conference table, then through a service hallway that smelled of fryer oil from above, and then into the waste sorting room. Mateo Valverde had walked this corner of the back-of-house exactly three times in nine days. Each time, the bins had been more full than the last. Each time, the little compactor in the corner had been waiting on a part from the mainland.", "Now the service route forced them through waste sorting.", "Mateo Valverde hated that the little animals made sense there.", "Food scraps in white bags. Meat trimmings in red bags. Fruit rinds. Disposable cups. A whole tray of dessert squares tipped into a bin because some guest event had ended faster than planned. The back of the park had set a table for scavengers.", "One climbed onto a bag and looked at him.", "Then Mateo Valverde saw the rest.", "Not one. A room full.", "Three on the long bin against the wall. Two more behind the cardboard bale. Heads moving in and out of torn plastic. A pair tugging at the same red bag from opposite ends. Bright eyes everywhere he turned the flashlight. Narrow heads. Small bodies. Plenty of them.", "Mateo Valverde read the room the way he read any other.", "The bin liners had not been changed. The drain grates had not been raked. The compactor had not been run. A red bag near the door had been open long enough that the meat inside had gone the color a sanitation worker did not want to think about. The smell was warm. Warm meant time. Time meant these animals had been eating in this room for hours, maybe longer. They were not lost. They were boarders.", "He counted nine. Then he counted again, because the shadows behind the bale had moved, and counted twelve.", "Pest-control problem. Not monster problem. Same thing in the end.", "\"Do not kick them,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"I was not going to kick them.\"", "\"Everyone kicks small things when afraid.\"", "Rosa swore in a way her father would not have approved of.", "Mateo Valverde opened a cabinet and found powdered disinfectant, a spray wand, and a broken face shield. He poured disinfectant into a mop bucket and added water until the room stank sharp enough to make Rosa cough. The disinfectant was the kind hospitals used in surgery when a man had bled too much and the floor needed to look like a thing that had not had blood on it ten minutes earlier. Mateo Valverde knew the smell. The little animals would know it too, soon, and would learn it the way scavengers always learned a smell that had once preceded a thing not worth approaching.", "Then he pushed the bucket ahead of them with the rolling cart.", "The little animals backed away from the smell.", "Not far.", "Far enough.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Small scavenging dinosaurs pulling away from a yellow mop bucket of harsh disinfectant, white chemical mist rising, Mateo and Rosa edging past torn red biohazard bags toward a service door."}, "Halfway across the room, Rosa slipped.", "Mateo Valverde caught her before she hit the floor. The mop handle clattered away. The clatter was loud. The clatter was the kind of loud that a man cleaning a back room learned not to make, and the kind of loud he would never have made in this room on a normal night, but this was not a normal night, and Rosa's leg had not been a normal leg for forty minutes.", "Every little head turned.", "Mateo Valverde threw the disinfectant bucket.", "The bucket hit the floor between the bags and burst white chemical water across the tile. The animals scattered. One did not scatter fast enough. It screamed. Not loudly. Not like a movie animal. Like a kettle pushed off a stove.", "More answered from behind the bins. The answers were the answers of small animals to a small animal in distress, the kind of answer a hen made when a chick had been startled, the kind of answer that would have meant nothing to a man who had not yet learned that these particular small animals were not the kind whose answer a man wanted to be near.", "Rosa got her feet under her.", "\"Move,\" Rosa said.", "They moved.", "The cart wheel that had pulled left earlier in the kitchen pulled left here too. Mateo Valverde leaned against it with his hip and kept the bucket in front of them like a low fence between their shoes and the bags. The little animals followed at a distance the disinfectant allowed. One came too close. Mateo Valverde did not swing at it. He raised the spray wand. The animal stopped, considered, and stepped back.", "It had learned something already.", "Animals on this island learned fast.", "Animals on this island had been built fast.", "At the far door, Mateo Valverde saw red smears crossing the threshold ahead of them. Human blood or animal blood. He could not tell. He could tell where it went. The smears led toward the service corridor they needed.", "Blood trails were maps too.", "The little animals knew how to read them.", "Mateo Valverde looked at Rosa. Rosa looked at the smears. Neither of them said the thing that was in both of their heads, which was that the smears had to lead somewhere, and that the somewhere was either a person who had stopped bleeding because the bleeding had been stopped for them or a person who had stopped bleeding because the bleeding had been stopped by them.", "Either way, they were going to walk through it.", "The cart wheel pulled left.", "They went right."]},
  21: {"n": 21, "title": "Chapter 21: Quarantine Route", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A blue-lit raptor quarantine corridor outside double doors, cloudy plastic curtain strips visible through the glass, wet floor tape peeling, Jophery's route sheet held in a hand smeared with disinfectant."}, "The quarantine route did not start with a door.", "It started with a smell.", "Not rot. Not meat. Not disinfectant. Something medicinal under wet fur. {{Mateo Valverde}} knew it from hospital cages where dogs woke badly from surgery, and from the back of a vet's clinic where a sick goat had been left under a heat lamp because it would not have survived the truck home. He stopped before the blue double doors and put his hand flat against the wall.", "Cold vibration.", "Fans were running on the other side.", "Rosa stood behind him with one shoulder against a pipe. Her face had gone the color of paper that had been wet and dried wrong. The bandage above her knee had soaked through. She was holding the mop handle with two hands now because one hand was no longer doing the thing two hands could do.", "\"Tell me this is not the only way,\" Rosa said.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the route sheet.", "The clean exterior route was crossed out. The helipad stair had no handle. The guest corridor had children, {{raptors}}, or both. The kitchen was no longer a kitchen in any useful sense.", "\"It is not the only way.\"", "Rosa waited.", "\"It is the shortest bad way.\"", "{{Jophery Brown}} had written one line beside the quarantine doors:", "NEVER ALONE HERE.", "Mateo Valverde showed her.", "\"Good,\" Rosa said. \"Then you are following instructions.\"", "Jophery Brown's badge opened the first door. The room beyond was a changing vestibule. Hooks on the wall. Masks on the hooks. Yellow boots in a row. A shower head hung from the ceiling like a question. The second door had no reader. It had a wheel lock.", "Mateo Valverde turned it slowly.", "The wheel squealed.", "Everything behind the door stopped moving.", "That was worse than noise.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A quarantine changing vestibule with yellow rubber boots in a row, hanging respirator masks, a ceiling-mounted shower head, and a heavy wheel-lock door stenciled DO NOT PROP OPEN."}, "They entered between plastic curtain strips gone cloudy from scratches.", "The room was wider than it should have been. Mateo Valverde counted steps without thinking. Twelve to the far wall, maybe fourteen with Rosa's leg. Cages lined both sides. The ceiling was low enough that the fans seemed closer than they should. The light was blue-white and unkind. It made Rosa's bandage look black and Mateo Valverde's hands look like they belonged to a man already dead.", "The cages were not large. Transport cages. Medical cages. Each had a clipboard wired to the door.", "Mateo Valverde moved past them and read tags as he went.", "Most were blank.", "One had a species number he did not know.", "One was handwritten.", "BITES LATCHES.", "He stopped on that one.", "An animal that learned hardware was a different problem. He looked back at the wheel lock on the door behind them. He looked at the shower head in the vestibule. He understood now why the vestibule had a drain in the floor.", "They were supposed to hose off whatever made it out before it made it any further.", "The floor drain in the room ran backward.", "Black water pushed up through the grate in slow pulses. Mateo Valverde crouched.", "A feather floated up.", "Then a second feather, smaller, paler.", "Then a strip of gauze, white at one end, pink at the other.", "\"Keep your foot out of that,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Rosa made a sound through her teeth. The sound was the sound of a woman who had decided not to be afraid out loud, and who had been holding the decision long enough that the decision had begun to cost her.", "The drain pulsed again.", "They kept moving.", "Halfway through the room, something tapped the inside of an empty cage.", "Mateo Valverde turned the flashlight.", "Nothing inside.", "Tap.", "The sound came again. Not from the cage.", "From the air vent above it.", "He raised the light.", "The grille was a standard ventilation cover. Four screws. Painted white. The kind he had taken off and put back a hundred times in service corridors. Four-inch screws, Phillips head, painted over once when the wall had been painted, the paint cracking now around the screw heads where the screws had begun to turn against it.", "The screws were turning.", "One. Then the next. Slow. Even. A hand on the other side that knew what a Phillips head was for.", "Or not a hand.", "A hooked claw, working in the rhythm a claw worked in when the claw had once turned a similar screw on a smaller grille and had remembered what the grille came off for.", "Rosa said, \"Mateo.\"", "The sound stopped.", "Mateo Valverde did not move. Rosa did not move. The fans kept running. The drain pulsed once more. The blue-white light buzzed. He counted in his head. He had read once that a man's heart slowed when a man held very still. His did not slow. He counted his pulse against the buzzing of the light. The pulse was faster than the buzzing. The buzzing was steady. The pulse was not.", "Then the screws began again.", "That was worse.", "Worse not because the screws were faster, but because the thing on the other side of the grille had decided that the human voice from the room had been a thing it could ignore. A small predator that turned away from a voice was a predator that had not yet learned about people. A small predator that did not turn away was a predator that had already seen one or two of them.", "Mateo Valverde looked at Rosa. Rosa looked at the grille. Then she looked at the mop handle, which was wood, which was nothing, and at her own bad leg, which would not run.", "She lifted her chin toward the far door.", "He nodded.", "They began to move toward the door without taking their eyes off the grille.", "The screws kept turning."]},
  22: {"n": 22, "title": "Chapter 22: Counting Error", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A personnel accountability terminal in a dark service office, green text listing BROWN ACTIVE and VALVERDE DEPARTED while rain beats the window glass."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} held the vent grille in place with the mop handle while Rosa turned the screws back in by hand.", "The thing in the vent pushed once.", "Rosa said, \"Do not let go.\"", "\"I had not planned to.\"", "The screws were wet. Her fingers were wet. The animal behind the metal found the gap at the corner and put one claw through. The claw hooked the air. It missed Mateo Valverde's sleeve by two fingers. It vanished when Rosa got the last screw to bite. The claw was the size of the curl of a man's index finger. It was wet. It had a black tip the way a bird's beak was black at the tip. It was not a bird's claw.", "They did not wait to see if it held.", "The quarantine route let out behind the personnel accountability office. That name was printed on the door in calm black letters, the kind of letters a building used when the building wanted a worker to feel that the room behind the door was an orderly room, even if the room behind the door was not. Inside were two desks, one dead computer, one living terminal. A wall board ran the length of the back wall.", "Magnetic names. Three columns.", "ON SITE.", "EVACUATED.", "UNACCOUNTED.", "Mateo Valverde read the board the way he had learned to read {{Jophery Brown}}'s route sheet. As data. He counted ON SITE first. Eleven magnets. Then EVACUATED. Forty-three. Then UNACCOUNTED.", "Twenty-two.", "The numbers did not match the column header above them. Someone had drawn a line under the first nine names in EVACUATED and written PRINTED CONFIRM. The thirty-four below had no line. Pencil marks beside some. Question marks beside others.", "Rosa stood at his shoulder. \"What are you doing?\"", "\"Counting.\"", "\"Why?\"", "\"Because the system is.\"", "He found {{Tomás Araya}} under UNACCOUNTED. Magnet, no pencil. Just the name pressed into the felt. The pressed-into part was the part that hurt. A man becoming a name on felt. A man with a permanent badge and a moustache and a flashlight wrapped in black tape, a man who had said <i>forget half of what Haskins told you</i>, becoming a magnet on the wrong side of a board.", "He found Rosa under EVACUATED. Magnet, no line. Pencil mark beside her last name. The pencil mark was a check, then a question mark drawn over the check.", "He found himself.", "EVACUATED. Pencil. Crossed once. Someone had written BOAT in small letters next to the cross.", "He touched the mark.", "The pencil told him a thing the print could not. Whoever wrote BOAT had not been sure. Print meant confirmation. Pencil meant guess. They had guessed him onto the boat because guessing was easier than calling the dock. The pencil writer had not been a bad person. The pencil writer had been a person at the end of a long shift who needed to be done with a clipboard before the boat left.", "He looked for Jophery Brown.", "No magnet.", "No pencil.", "No dead column for men who had been eaten by a failure everyone signed.", "The living terminal blinked behind him.", "ACCOUNTABILITY RECONCILIATION IN PROGRESS.", "Mateo Valverde pressed the arrow key.", "PERMANENT STAFF ACTIVE: BROWN, JOPHERY. TEMPORARY CONTRACTORS REMAINING: 0. ACTION: CORRECT MISMATCH?", "No was not an option.", "Only ENTER.", "He did not press it.", "The terminal pressed itself after ten seconds.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A magnetic evacuation board shows Rosa marked evacuated, Tomás unaccounted, Mateo penciled as BOAT, and no place at all for Jophery Brown."}, "The printer began.", "CORRECTION APPLIED. VALVERDE, MATEO. DEPARTED EAST DOCK. BROWN, JOPHERY. ACTIVE SERVICE RESPONSE.", "Mateo Valverde tore the paper so hard it ripped through the line with his name.", "He did not say anything.", "He did not have a sentence for what the system had just done. The system had taken a thing the boat manifest had guessed and turned the guess into a fact, and the fact was now what the building remembered, and the building's memory was the only memory that mattered when the building was the only thing left to remember.", "Rosa did not tell him to calm down.", "That made him trust her more.", "\"We can take the board,\" Rosa said.", "\"What?\"", "\"The magnets. The paper. Your crossed-out name.\"", "\"For who?\"", "\"For whoever tries to say you were never here.\"", "He looked at her. Her trouser leg was black. Her face was wet. She had walked half a building with one bad leg, and her first thought, in a room with a board that had erased a man, had been to bring the board with them. Mateo Valverde understood, the way he had understood Tomás Araya the night they had met in the corridor, that he had been lucky in the people who had decided to find him on this island.", "He pulled his magnet off the felt. Then Rosa's. Then Tomás Araya's.", "He folded the torn reconciliation page into the plastic sleeve with Jophery Brown's complaint.", "The terminal chimed.", "NEW SERVICE RESPONSE ASSIGNED.", "{{RAPTOR}} SERVICE ENTRY D-17. BROWN, JOPHERY REPORT IMMEDIATELY.", "Mateo Valverde turned back to the wall.", "The space where Tomás Araya's magnet had been was empty felt.", "He stared at the empty square long enough for Rosa to say his name once.", "Then the magnet for Tomás Araya slid by itself across the board, from where it was no longer, and settled into a fourth column that had not been there a minute ago.", "LOCKED IN ZONE.", "The column had not been on the board when they walked in.", "The column was on the board now, in the same handwriting as the original three columns, and in the same paint, as if the column had always been there and Mateo Valverde had simply not been looking at it.", "Rosa took a step back.", "\"That was not a person doing that,\" Rosa said.", "\"No.\"", "\"Then what was it?\"", "Mateo Valverde watched the magnet sit in its new column. The magnet did not move again. The terminal printed nothing else. The fans in the next room kept running. The drain in the quarantine room kept pulsing under a closed door.", "\"It was the building,\" Mateo Valverde said, \"deciding it was running out of places to put us.\""]},
  23: {"n": 23, "title": "Chapter 23: Raptor Silence", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A silent staff corridor outside raptor service, wet floor reflecting yellow emergency strips, three doors cracked open and a black badge reader at the far end."}, "The {{raptor}} service corridor had gone quiet.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} had never heard it quiet before.", "Even empty, the place had made noises. Fans. Drains. Distant relays. Men coughing into radios. The raptors themselves, sometimes. A bark or a scrape from behind layers of steel and mesh. Workplaces had sounds. Sounds told you which machines still cared.", "Now there was only water.", "Drip from the ceiling.", "Runoff under the door.", "Rosa breathing through pain beside him.", "Mateo Valverde held {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge away from his chest so it would not tap the plastic sleeve with every breath. He had begun to hate that little sound. It announced him to machines. It announced a dead man to doors. It announced a debt he had not yet agreed to take on, and which the badge had begun to collect anyway.", "D-17 stood at the end of the hall.", "The reader with the bad complaint.", "The reader Jophery Brown had reported.", "The reader that might open to {{Tomás Araya}}, or to nothing a person should enter.", "\"We do this fast,\" Rosa whispered.", "\"Fast breaks things.\"", "\"Slow gets eaten.\"", "Both true.", "They moved.", "Mateo Valverde went first along the wall. He put his right shoulder against the tile. He kept his left hand on the badge sleeve to stop it knocking. He set each boot heel down before the toe so the heel would catch grit before the toe could slide. Old kitchen rule. Still worked. The bar in Puntarenas had taught him that rule the first month, when the cook had watched him slip on fish water and had said <i>heel before toe, Maecillo, men with bad knees taught me the same thing on a boat</i>.", "The first raptor door was open.", "Not wide. Not broken. Open three inches, held by the automatic latch as if someone had asked politely. Mateo Valverde shone the flashlight at the gap and stopped the beam at the seam. He did not put the beam through. A flashlight inside a holding room was a flashlight whose location was now known to whatever was in the holding room.", "Empty smell. Straw. Bleach. Something under bleach.", "He moved past it without looking inside.", "Rosa came behind him on the bad leg. She slid her shoulder along the tile and slid her boot a hand's width at a time. Her jaw was set on her own breath. She did not make the breath into a sound. She used the breath to time the steps. He had seen women time pain that way at the hospital, on the night his mother had broken her wrist in the bathroom. Pain had a tempo. The tempo was the only thing a person controlled.", "The second door was open too.", "So was the third.", "No alarms.", "No red lights.", "The fans inside the holding rooms were not running. That was how he knew. The raptors lived under blown air. The blown air had stopped. The blown air did not stop unless the room did not need it.", "Quiet had a shape now.", "It was every door that should have been closed.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Three raptor service doors stand open three inches each, yellow warning labels darkened by water, a badge reader at the corridor end reflecting a man's face."}, "At D-17, the reader screen was black.", "Mateo Valverde saw his own face in it. Wet hair. Split lip he did not remember getting. One eye wide enough to look foolish. The reflection was not a man he recognized. It was a man on the seventh hour of the wrong day, and the seventh hour had taken something out of his face that the first six had not been told to take.", "Behind his reflection, a second shape lifted its head.", "He did not turn.", "Turning took time.", "He grabbed Rosa by the front of her shirt and shoved her into the wall recess beside the reader. The recess was a hand deep. It was meant for a fire extinguisher. The extinguisher was gone.", "The raptor struck the corridor where her body had been.", "The animal hit tile and corrected without slipping.", "That was the terrible part.", "Everything else slipped here. Men. Carts. Water. Mateo Valverde. The raptor's feet found the floor like it had read it better than he ever would. The animal weighed what a man weighed, but it did not weigh that across a man's shape. It weighed it across two narrow feet, and the two narrow feet redistributed the weight in a way that ignored water on tile the way a fish ignored water in a sea.", "Mateo Valverde slapped Jophery Brown's badge against D-17.", "Nothing.", "He slapped it again. The badge rang flat against the panel like a coin on a counter. The flat ring was the sound a dead man's badge made when the building had finally been told that the dead man was dead.", "The animal lowered its head.", "It lowered its head with the patience of a thing that had decided where the next bite was going to be, and was now closing the distance to that bite at the speed the bite required.", "The reader chirped green.", "Not from Mateo Valverde's side.", "From the other side of the door.", "The chirp was small. The chirp was not the chirp of a reader being struck by a badge. The chirp was the chirp of a reader being granted access by a hand that was on the other side and that knew which surface of the reader to touch.", "The door began to open.", "Two inches.", "Three.", "Wide enough for a man to slip through.", "Wide enough for a raptor.", "Mateo Valverde did not know yet which one would go first."]},
  24: {"n": 24, "title": "Chapter 24: Full Reboot", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A raptor service reader flickering red to green during a full system reboot, Mateo's temporary badge held against the panel while Jophery's badge dangles from his other hand."}, "The door opened inward.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} fell through it because he had been leaning into the reader, expecting failure. Rosa fell after him. The {{raptor}}'s jaw closed on the mop handle instead of her leg. Wood cracked. Rosa let go.", "The door shut.", "For one second the raptor was on the other side and they were alive.", "Then every light in the room went white.", "Not emergency white. Full white. Office white. Visitor-center white. The white of systems pretending nothing bad had happened because electricity had returned and electricity made cowards confident.", "A chime sounded through the room.", "FULL SYSTEM REBOOT COMPLETE.", "The speaker voice was cheerful. The voice was the same voice that had read evacuation announcements in two languages, but the voice had been given a different sentence to read now, and the voice was reading it in the same untroubled tone, because the voice did not know whether the men outside the speaker were alive.", "Mateo Valverde hated it more than the alarms.", "Rosa lay on her side, panting. \"Tell me that helps.\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at the reader inside the room.", "{{Jophery Brown}}'s badge: red.", "His temporary badge: red.", "He tried Jophery Brown's again.", "Red.", "The display read:", "INVALID - DECEASED EMPLOYEE.", "Mateo Valverde stared at it.", "He stared at it because the building had taken back the only thing the building had ever given him in the past four hours. The dead man's name had been a door. Now the dead man's name was a closed file with a stamp on it.", "Rosa said, \"They fixed it.\"", "\"No.\"", "\"What do you mean no?\"", "\"They fixed the dead man.\"", "He put his temporary badge flat to the reader. This time the display did not reject it. It searched. The searching took long enough for the raptor outside to put one claw into the gap below the door and pull. The metal at the bottom of the door peeled up the way a soda-can lid peeled up under a thumbnail. A line of corridor light became visible under the bottom edge.", "The display changed.", "TEMP PROFILE CACHE FOUND.", "Mateo Valverde stopped breathing.", "VALID FOR LOCAL EXIT ONLY. VALVERDE, MATEO.", "Green.", "He read his own name on the green display and felt something move in his chest that was not relief. It was the colder thing that came after relief, the thing that recognized that the building had decided to remember him only because the building had decided, in some other room, that remembering him was now safe.", "The cache had not found him.", "The cache had been <i>given</i> him.", "Someone, somewhere, had fed his profile back into the local table. Someone had wanted Mateo Valverde to have a green light at this exact reader at this exact minute, and had decided what kind of green light Mateo Valverde was allowed to have, which was a local-exit green, not a corridor green.", "Someone had limited him.", "Someone was watching.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A beige reader display reads TEMP PROFILE CACHE FOUND / VALVERDE, MATEO while a raptor claw scrapes the bottom seam of the door and curls metal up."}, "He hit the open button.", "The wrong door opened.", "Not the corridor door. A rear service hatch behind them. The system had given Mateo Valverde what he was allowed to have, not what he wanted. Local exit. One way. No choice.", "He dragged Rosa through the hatch as the raptor peeled metal at the corridor door.", "The hatch dropped them into a narrow records room behind raptor service. Metal shelves to the ceiling. Old forms. Dead monitors. Boxes stacked three deep along one wall, each labeled INCIDENT VIDEO - DO NOT DUPLICATE. The shelves smelled of dust that had become paste, which was the smell of paper that had been wet at some point in its life and had decided to remember the wetness afterward.", "Mateo Valverde's flashlight crossed one box at eye level. The label had a date eight years before opening. An animal designation in code. The word RESTRICTED stamped twice. Beside it, a smaller box had a date six months before this storm, and a designation he could read: V.RAPTOR / TRANSFER / FATALITY.", "He did not stop. He did not read past it. The beam moved on. There was time later for boxes. There was no time now for anything but a door.", "One monitor woke when the reboot reached it.", "It showed a map.", "Two dots.", "VALVERDE, M. - LOCAL EXIT BROWN, J. - DECEASED", "The map sat on the screen.", "Mateo Valverde lowered Rosa onto a folded canvas drop cloth.", "Rosa pressed her hand under her bad knee and held it. Her face was paler than it had been in the quarantine room. Her hands had begun to shake the small shake hands made when the body had decided that the leg was not getting enough blood and the rest of the body was going to keep more for itself.", "Mateo Valverde found the room's only other exit, a service door with a manual lever, and put his weight against the lever to test the spring. The spring was strong. The spring was older than the rest of the door. The spring would let them out and would not let anything else follow on its own, the way old springs did when the spring had been the part nobody had thought to upgrade.", "The map zoomed.", "TRANSMITTING LOCATION TO CENTRAL SECURITY.", "For the first time all night, the park knew where Mateo Valverde was.", "He did not know whether being known was a thing he should be glad of or a thing he should be afraid of.", "He looked at Rosa.", "Rosa looked at the map.", "\"Whoever they are,\" Rosa said, \"they remembered you on purpose.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Do we trust that.\"", "Mateo Valverde watched the map blink.", "He thought about the strip of blue cloth on the valve wheel.", "He thought about the limited green at the reader.", "He thought about {{Tomás Araya}}'s magnet sliding into a column that had not existed.", "\"Not yet,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "He pulled the manual lever.", "The door opened away from the map."]},
  25: {"n": 25, "title": "Chapter 25: After the Click", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A records room behind raptor service, shelves of incident tapes stacked three deep, an open service hatch above, and a monitor still transmitting a location dot."}, "After the click, the park woke in pieces.", "Not the right pieces.", "Fans came on in rooms with open doors. Locks cycled in empty halls. Freezer alarms reset. A phone rang under a desk no one could reach. Somewhere above {{raptor}} service, sprinklers began spraying water over concrete already wet enough to shine. The building had been told to wake up. The building had not been told what was supposed to be in its rooms.", "The records-room monitor kept transmitting {{Mateo Valverde}}'s location.", "Rosa smashed it with the tape box.", "The screen died.", "The little green transmit light on the CPU stayed on.", "\"That did not work,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "\"I noticed.\"", "He yanked the power cord. The green light died.", "From the corridor outside came the clean sound of a lock opening.", "Rosa looked at him.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the only other door.", "It had a manual latch and a deadbolt. The latch opened. The deadbolt did not. He used the wrench. The wrench slipped and took skin from his knuckles. He did not feel it until blood made the handle slick. He felt it then, briefly, the way a man felt small injuries on a night when the small injuries were the smallest thing about the night.", "\"Mateo.\"", "\"I know.\"", "\"Mateo.\"", "\"I know.\"", "The deadbolt gave.", "They went through into a hall lined with staff lockers. The hall was beige. The lockers were green. The fluorescent strip in the ceiling was on for the first three meters of the hall and off for the last six, the way fluorescent strips were when the building had been told to keep its peripherals on but had been low on the kind of attention a hallway needed.", "Halfway down, a man sat against the wall with a radio in his lap.", "{{Tomás Araya}}.", "Mateo Valverde stopped so hard Rosa hit his back.", "Tomás Araya opened one eye.", "\"Temporary,\" Tomás Araya said.", "Mateo Valverde dropped beside him.", "Tomás Araya had a bite high on one arm and a bad cut across his side where something metal, not teeth, had opened him. He had tied a belt around the arm. The belt was wrong. Too low. Too loose. Work done one-handed in the dark by a man whose other hand had stopped doing what it was supposed to do.", "Mateo Valverde reached for the buckle to tighten it.", "Tomás Araya pulled the arm back.", "Not violently. Just the firmness of a man who had decided.", "Mateo Valverde tried once more.", "\"Don't.\"", "Not loud. Just final.", "Mateo Valverde's hand stopped above the belt and did not come down.", "He understood then. The way a man understood when he watched someone else's hand make a small choice that had a large meaning behind it. Tomás Araya had tied the belt the wrong way because the belt was for show. The belt was for Mateo Valverde's eyes when Mateo Valverde came around the corner. The belt was so a friend would not have to hear the friend say the thing the belt said for him.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Tomás Araya slumped beside green staff lockers with a radio in his lap, one arm belted wrong, emergency light catching wet tile and a fresh smear under his side."}, "\"Can you stand?\" Mateo Valverde asked.", "\"No.\"", "\"We can carry—\"", "\"No.\"", "Tomás Araya looked at Rosa. \"You are supposed to be on a boat.\"", "\"Everyone keeps telling me,\" Rosa said.", "The corridor lock behind them clicked again.", "Tomás Araya pushed his permanent badge into Mateo Valverde's hand. The badge was warm from his palm and scratched almost white at the edges, the way Mateo Valverde had first seen it on the night they had met outside the briefing room.", "\"No.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"We have {{Jophery Brown}}'s.\"", "\"Dead now. System knows. Mine still has animal-service override.\"", "\"Then we take you.\"", "Tomás Araya grabbed Mateo Valverde's sleeve with his good hand. His grip was weak. That made it worse.", "\"You take the living woman who can walk badly. You take the papers. You tell my sister I stayed mean to the end.\"", "\"No.\"", "Tomás Araya smiled with one side of his mouth. \"Temporary means go when the boat is leaving.\"", "Mateo Valverde tried to say a sentence. The sentence did not finish. Tomás Araya patted his hand once, the small pat of a man who had run out of speeches and was using touch instead.", "\"Maecillo,\" Tomás Araya said. \"Listen.\"", "Mateo Valverde listened.", "\"You watched the floor,\" Tomás Araya said. \"You read the bag. You bagged the cloth. You folded a map. I watched you do those things. Men do those things who go home. You are going home.\"", "\"I am not.\"", "\"You are. Do not argue with a dying man. It is impolite.\"", "Tomás Araya laughed without sound. The laugh moved his side. The side bled under the wrong belt.", "The door at the end of the locker hall opened.", "Tomás Araya shoved his badge harder into Mateo Valverde's hand. The shove was the strongest thing his arm had done in a minute, and would be the strongest thing his arm did again.", "Tomás Araya's eyes did not close. They went to the locker across from him with the rust line under its number. He kept them there. The locker was Jophery Brown's. Mateo Valverde understood that too, in the small slow way understandings came at the end of long nights. Tomás Araya had decided where he was going to be when he stopped being. He had picked a hallway with the dead man's locker in it. He had picked the company.", "Mateo Valverde took the badge because needing things was uglier than refusing them.", "He did not say goodbye.", "A man who said goodbye to Tomás Araya was a man who had decided Tomás Araya was already gone, and Mateo Valverde was not going to be the one to decide that for him.", "Rosa touched his shoulder.", "They went.", "Behind them, Tomás Araya sat against the locker wall with the radio in his lap and his eyes on a strip of black tape with neat square letters on it across the corridor.", "The locker hall light flickered once, the way it had flickered the first time Mateo Valverde had walked under it.", "He did not look back.", "He did not need to.", "The hall was inside him already, the way Tomás Araya had been inside him since the first night, and would be inside him for as long as Mateo Valverde walked any other hall, anywhere, ever."]},
  26: {"n": 26, "title": "Chapter 26: Kitchen Without Children", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "The Visitor Center kitchen after the attack, stainless counters streaked, a ladle under the stove line, freezer fog along the seam and raptor claw marks down a cabinet door."}, "The kitchen had no children in it.", "That was the first mercy.", "It had everything children left behind.", "Muddy prints on tile. A ladle under the stove line. A cabinet door hanging crooked. A pan dented where something had stepped on it. On the stainless counter, one small handprint in condensation, already fading because the freezer air had begun to warm.", "{{Mateo Valverde}} looked at the handprint too long.", "The handprint was the size of a six-year-old's hand. The fingers had been spread the way a child spread fingers when a child was trying to keep balance against something cold. The thumb was the print of a child who had not yet learned to keep a thumb tucked when a thumb was about to be in danger, and that was the only thing about the handprint Mateo Valverde could read as luck. The child had been afraid but not bitten. The thumb had been on the steel, not in a mouth.", "Rosa touched his arm. \"They got out.\"", "\"You know?\"", "\"No.\"", "It was an honest answer, which meant it helped.", "They had come back through the kitchen because {{Tomás Araya}}'s badge opened animal-service doors but not guest stairwells, and because the service spine to North Maintenance ran under the dish pit. Mateo Valverde did not think about Tomás Araya after that sentence. He put the thought on a shelf. The shelf was wet. The shelf would break later.", "For now, kitchen.", "He read it like work.", "Freezer door scraped at bottom: opened hard, then blocked.", "Shelf knocked down but not collapsed: animal weight near edge, not full body.", "Food torn, not eaten: distraction.", "Water under dishwasher moving toward the wrong drain: storm line failing.", "Fryer oil cooled in the fryer: nobody had pulled the basket. A cook always pulled the basket before he walked away. The cook had not walked away. The cook had run.", "The {{raptors}} had learned the room faster than the people who built the room.", "Rosa leaned on the prep counter. \"What are you doing?\"", "\"Trying not to step where they stepped.\"", "\"Why?\"", "\"Because they did not slip.\"", "The freezer bumped once.", "Both of them looked.", "The walk-in door was closed from the outside with a serving cart wedged under the handle. Frost melted down the seam. The seam was wet. A wet seam was a seam that had been opening and closing for some time, in small motions, by something whose weight had not been enough to break the wedge of the cart.", "Rosa lifted the mop handle she had taken from Tomás Araya's hall. \"Do we open it?\"", "Mateo Valverde listened.", "Another bump. Weak.", "Not claws.", "Knuckles.", "The knuckles were the knuckles of a hand that had been trying to be heard for a while and had stopped trying very hard, the way a hand inside a freezer was when the hand had used most of its heat already.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A walk-in freezer door wedged shut by a stainless serving cart, frost melting down the seam, the handle vibrating where a fist taps from inside."}, "He moved the cart.", "A man fell out with the cold.", "Not a guest. Not security. Kitchen whites under a rain jacket. His lips were blue and one eyebrow had frozen stiff with blood. He blinked at Mateo Valverde and tried to say something, but his jaw shook too hard.", "Rosa and Mateo Valverde dragged him behind the counter.", "\"Name,\" Rosa said.", "\"Luis,\" the man managed.", "\"Can you walk?\"", "He laughed once, which became a cough. \"Everyone asks.\"", "Mateo Valverde wrapped him in two tablecloths and hated every second that used time. The tablecloths smelled of starch and lemon. The man inside the tablecloths smelled of cold and of the inside of a freezer where meat had begun to go warm and then cold again. Luis was missing the tip of one finger. The tip was old. The tip had not been taken tonight. It had been taken in another kitchen, in another decade, by a knife. Luis was a man whose hands had given pieces of themselves to kitchens his whole life. Mateo Valverde understood him already.", "Luis clutched his sleeve.", "\"North Dock,\" Luis said.", "Mateo Valverde froze.", "\"What about it?\"", "\"Maintenance launch. Fuel locker. Haskins sent two men.\"", "\"When?\"", "\"Before the phones died.\"", "\"Are they still there?\"", "\"I don't know. They had keys. They had a list. The list had four names on it.\"", "\"Four?\"", "\"They wrote them in pencil.\"", "Pencil again. Mateo Valverde almost laughed. The whole island was being run by pencil tonight. Pencil and guesses. Pencil and <i>PRINTED CONFIRM</i>. Pencil and <i>BOAT</i>. Pencil and four names on a list a kitchen man had seen when nobody was watching him.", "\"Whose names.\"", "\"I did not see whose. I saw the count.\"", "Rosa looked at Mateo Valverde.", "Mateo Valverde's hand on the tablecloth went slack for one second. He had stopped planning a route an hour ago. North Dock put a route back in his hand. Not a feeling. A tool. Something with edges he could grip wrong and still use.", "\"How far is North Dock from here?\" Rosa asked.", "\"Forty minutes,\" Luis said. \"On a good day. Through the service road. Past the pump station.\"", "\"Tonight?\"", "Luis did not answer.", "The freezer bumped again.", "Not from inside.", "From the door behind them, something copied the sound of a hand.", "The copy was not a fist. The copy was the back of a hooked claw. The animal had heard the knuckles. The animal was practicing. The animal had decided that the sound of a hand on metal was a sound that opened a door.", "Mateo Valverde looked at Rosa. Rosa looked at the door.", "Luis closed his eyes.", "\"Move,\" Luis whispered.", "They moved."]},
  27: {"n": 27, "title": "Chapter 27: North Dock Promise", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A hand-drawn route to North Dock spread on a kitchen counter beside Tomás's badge, Jophery's badge, and a cracked temporary badge with a melted corner."}, "North Dock was not on the guest map.", "It was on three bad maps and one good rumor.", "{{Jophery Brown}}'s route sheet showed a service road broken by a creek crossing. {{Tomás Araya}}'s badge opened animal-service gates along the first half. Luis knew the fuel locker code because kitchen deliveries used the north route when investors wanted the east dock to look clean. Rosa knew the radio phrase for a maintenance launch because she had signed boats out twice and been yelled at both times for writing too slowly.", "Between them, they had almost enough.", "Almost was a cruel word.", "Almost was the word that paid the rent if a man worked overtime and the doctor charged the same. Almost was a man at a fence with a stern light pulling away. Almost was the kind of word a careful man learned not to use, because almost was a sound a careful man's mouth made on the way to a different sound.", "Luis could walk if {{Mateo Valverde}} took most of his weight. Rosa could walk if she hated the floor enough. Mateo Valverde could walk because nobody had asked his body permission.", "They left the kitchen through the dish pit and came out under the visitor center loading dock. Dawn had not arrived. The night had thinned. Rain still fell. The big storm was moving off or saving strength. Mateo Valverde did not trust either possibility.", "The North Dock route began behind a gate marked MAINTENANCE ONLY.", "Tomás Araya's badge opened it.", "Mateo Valverde did not thank the machine.", "The service road beyond was narrow, cut through wet green walls. Twice they had to stop and listen. Once, a branch moved against the wind. Once, nothing moved at all and that was enough to make them crouch behind a utility cart until Luis started shaking from cold. Cold and the thing the body did under fear shared a tremor. Mateo Valverde could not tell which of Luis's tremors was which. He held him by the shoulders until the shaking became one kind of shaking again.", "Rosa kept her bad leg in the rut beside the road. The rut was deep. The rut held the leg straighter. She had figured that out without saying so, the way a woman figured out what kept her upright when nobody had time for instructions.", "At the creek crossing, the road was gone.", "Not flooded.", "Gone.", "Water had eaten the edge and dropped half the concrete into the channel. On the other side, the road continued as if nothing had happened because roads were stupid that way.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A washed-out service road creek crossing, broken concrete hanging over brown floodwater, three pipes strapped under the gap as a maintenance crossing."}, "Mateo Valverde found the old pipe bridge under the crossing.", "It was not meant for people. It was three pipes strapped to steel brackets, wet with spray, running over brown water full of branches. Jophery Brown had drawn it as a dotted line and written:", "IF YOU ARE SMALL AND STUPID.", "\"Good news,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Rosa looked at the pipes. \"No.\"", "\"It is on the map.\"", "\"That is not an argument.\"", "Luis laughed, then coughed until he had to sit. The cough was a kitchen man's cough. The cough had been earned over fryers, over hot dish steam, over the cold air of walk-ins entered too many times in a shift. The cough did not belong to a man who was supposed to cross a pipe bridge tonight.", "Mateo Valverde tied one end of the rope to the bracket on the near side. He looped the other end around his waist and held the slack in his teeth.", "\"Luis goes first,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "Rosa turned her head. \"He can barely stand.\"", "\"He weighs the least. He will not shift the brackets.\"", "Luis looked at the pipes. He did not say anything. He took the rope from Mateo Valverde's hand and started moving.", "He did not look down. He set one boot, then the next, knees bent the way kitchen men set crates onto wet tile. The pipes rolled a quarter inch under him. He kept going. Halfway across, his shoulders hitched once. He kept going. He reached the far bracket, sat down hard on concrete, and lifted one hand to show he was alive.", "Rosa breathed out through her teeth.", "\"My turn,\" Rosa said.", "She did not give Mateo Valverde time to argue.", "Her bad leg went on second. That was the part she could not hide. Each step started with the good leg testing pipe, then the bad leg dragging up beside it, weight passing across slow. Her face went tight at the corners of the mouth. Lips pressed flat. Jaw set the way a person set it before lifting something heavier than it should be.", "Her hands did not touch the rope.", "Her hands stayed on her own thighs.", "She walked her palms down her trousers in time with the bad leg, pressing against the muscle like she was telling it to keep going one more step. Press. Step. Press. Step. The pipes hissed under her boots. A branch hit the bracket downstream. She did not look at it.", "She reached the far side and sat next to Luis without making a sound.", "Mateo Valverde went last.", "Halfway across, the pipe bracket shifted. Not broke. Shifted. Enough to drop his left foot into open air and slam his knee against steel.", "He bit his hand so he would not shout.", "The rope went tight at his waist. Luis had it. Luis, who had not spoken in an hour, was on the bracket on the far side with both hands locked on the line and his weight thrown back against the steel. Luis weighed eighty kilos in a shower. Luis was holding the rope as if he weighed two hundred. The body found weight where the body had to.", "Mateo Valverde got his boot back onto the pipe. He crossed the rest in four bad steps. The bad steps were each their own bad step. None of them resembled the steps before them.", "On the far side, a radio fixed to a weather box crackled.", "\"North Dock,\" Rosa whispered.", "Mateo Valverde opened the box and lifted the handset.", "The handset was warm. The handset had been used in the last hour. Whoever was on the other end of this radio was awake and was nearby and was waiting.", "Mateo Valverde pressed the button.", "\"North Dock. This is service party on route. Three survivors.\"", "Static.", "Then a man's voice, close enough to hurt.", "\"Say name.\""]},
  28: {"n": 28, "title": "Chapter 28: The Wrong Dead Man", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "A weather-box radio under rain at the North Dock road end, handset in Mateo's hand, the small display asking SAY NAME while three survivors crouch below the pipe bridge."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} knew the right answer.", "That was the problem.", "He looked at Rosa. She had one hand on the rope around Luis and one hand on the pipe rail. She heard the voice. She heard the question. She also saw the badges on Mateo Valverde's lanyard: green temporary plastic, {{Jophery Brown}}'s cloudy permanent card, {{Tomás Araya}}'s scratched animal-service override.", "Three names hanging together at his chest. One of them his.", "Two of them dead.", "<i>Say name.</i>", "Mateo Valverde pressed the handset.", "\"Mateo Valverde.\"", "Static.", "The man's voice came back flatter. \"No active Valverde on island manifest.\"", "\"The manifest is wrong.\"", "\"Identify by active credential.\"", "Mateo Valverde closed his eyes.", "He thought about Carmen Vega's metal box with the padlock. He thought about the woman on the maintenance dispatch line who had said <i>this ticket is already closed</i>. He thought about a junior assistant in a borrowed office choosing the phrase <i>incident residue</i> off a list. He thought about the printer that had stamped COMPLETED onto Jophery Brown's nine-day-old complaint. He thought about a building that had decided what it remembered, and about the men who had decided to let the building do the deciding because the building was easier to argue with than the men.", "Rosa said, \"Mateo.\"", "Not warning. Not permission. Just his name, so one human being had said it before the machine took it.", "He pressed the button again.", "\"Jophery Brown.\"", "The radio clicked into a different channel at once.", "\"Brown, you are listed deceased.\"", "\"Then your list is half right.\"", "Silence.", "Luis whispered, \"Jesus.\"", "The man on the radio said, \"How many with you?\"", "\"Three. One injured transport. One kitchen staff hypothermic. One temporary contractor.\"", "\"Temporary contractor does not show.\"", "\"I know.\"", "\"North Dock launch has fuel for one crossing. Gate is locked under animal-service control. Approach lights are off. We can open for Brown.\"", "Mateo Valverde looked at Tomás Araya's badge.", "He looked at Rosa.", "Rosa looked at the road.", "\"Open for Brown,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "The words tasted bad.", "The words tasted like the way a man tasted a thing he had not yet swallowed but had decided not to spit out, because spitting it out cost more than swallowing.", "The gate on the far side of the road clicked so loudly they heard it through the rain.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A North Dock access gate in the distance unlocking under a red animal-service light while jungle rain runs across the service road."}, "They moved faster after that because shame was also a kind of fuel.", "The road narrowed. The jungle pressed close. Once, Rosa stopped and pointed to mud where three-toed tracks crossed the road and vanished into ferns. The tracks were not huge. They did not need to be. The depth told Mateo Valverde the animal had not been running. The animal had been stalking. Stalking left a different kind of print.", "Luis had his arm around Mateo Valverde's shoulder and was using Mateo Valverde's body as the hinge his bad knee did not have. Rosa walked behind them in the rut on her own. Nobody spoke because the air had begun to ask for more than speech, the way an air did before something the eye had not yet seen had moved.", "At the final bend, they saw North Dock lights.", "Two of them.", "Low yellow bulbs over a fuel shed.", "Not enough light for rescue.", "Enough for bait.", "The launch sat in black water beside the dock, small, white, and real. The hull had not been washed in some time. The bow line was tied with a knot Mateo Valverde could fault — a man in a hurry had passed it once instead of twice, and the loose tail of the line had dropped into the water and was floating.", "A man in a poncho stood near the launch with a shotgun pointed at the ground. He raised the gun when he saw them.", "\"Brown?\"", "Mateo Valverde stepped forward.", "He took two steps. The first step was the step a man took when he was about to lie. The second step was the step a man took when he had decided not to.", "\"No,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "The man's face changed.", "Behind the fuel shed, the jungle answered in a voice Mateo Valverde had heard only once before: not a roar, not a scream, a low testing bark that made every dock light tremble.", "The man with the shotgun lifted the gun toward Mateo Valverde.", "\"You said Brown.\"", "\"I said the name the machine wanted.\"", "\"You lied to a coordinator.\"", "\"I lied to a building.\"", "The barrel of the shotgun was a small black hole. Mateo Valverde had been looking at small black holes all night. The drain sump under the {{raptor}} service grate. The crack in the generator-shed wall. The freezer door the long head had pulled itself back through. A shotgun barrel was the same kind of small black hole. The difference was that the shotgun barrel was being held by a man who had a wife, somewhere, who was waiting for him on a different boat.", "\"Show me your badge,\" the man with the shotgun said.", "Mateo Valverde lifted the lanyard. All three badges hung from it.", "The man's eyes moved across the badges. Mateo Valverde watched the eyes. The eyes stopped on Tomás Araya's badge first, because Tomás Araya's badge was the one that would have opened the gate. The eyes stopped on Jophery Brown's second, because Jophery Brown's name had been the one in the radio. The eyes stopped on Mateo Valverde's last, because Mateo Valverde's name was the one no machine had wanted to read.", "The eyes did not lift from the third badge for a longer time than the eyes had spent on the first two.", "\"Valverde,\" the man said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"You walked from raptor service to here on dead men's badges.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"With these two.\"", "\"Yes.\"", "\"How did you get past D-17.\"", "\"Tomás Araya's override. He gave it to me before he died.\"", "The man with the shotgun did not move. The rain did. The dock lights did. The jungle behind the fuel shed did. The animal in the jungle had stopped barking, which was not the relief it should have been, because an animal that had been barking and was no longer barking was an animal that had decided the barking had finished its work.", "The man's gun had not gone down.", "Rosa stepped between Mateo Valverde and the gun.", "\"Lower it,\" Rosa said.", "\"Step aside, ma'am.\"", "\"No.\"", "\"Ma'am.\"", "\"My name is Rosa Aguilar. I signed your launch out two months ago. I was the one who yelled at you for fueling fast. You yelled back. We laughed about it later. Lower the gun.\"", "The man's eyes flicked to her. The eyes did not finish the trip across her face before the bark came again, closer this time, much closer, from the trees behind the fuel shed.", "The man pivoted toward the trees.", "The shotgun was no longer pointing at Mateo Valverde.", "The animal came out of the ferns at the run.", "Not a raptor. Smaller. Two of them. Goat-sized. The same kind that had been at the pump house. They came low, fast, in the wedge a small predator used when there were two of them and the prey was three. They had decided which of the four humans was hurt and which were upright. They had decided in the time it took the man with the shotgun to turn his head.", "They went for Luis.", "The shotgun went off.", "The first animal flipped sideways and lay still in the gravel. The second animal did not stop. It hit Luis low. Luis dropped Mateo Valverde's shoulder and went down on one knee. He swung the rope, the only thing in his hand, and hit the animal's snout with the metal hook on the rope's end. The animal screamed.", "Mateo Valverde tackled it.", "He was not fighting it. He was throwing himself across Luis. The animal was under him for one second. He felt small ribs through the fabric of his coverall. He felt teeth in his sleeve, not in his arm. He felt the animal try to push itself out from under him with the strong back legs, and he held on the way a sanitation contractor held on to a thing that was thrashing in a bag he could not afford to open.", "Then the animal stopped.", "Rosa had the wrench.", "She had brought it down twice on the back of the animal's head. Twice was enough. The animal went limp.", "The man with the shotgun was reloading.", "He was reloading because two more of the animals were coming out of the trees.", "\"Boat,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "He did not shout it. He had no air to shout. He said it the way men said things in a kitchen when smoke meant you needed to leave the line.", "They went.", "Rosa took Luis's good arm. Mateo Valverde took the bad. They half-carried him over the last twelve meters of dock and dropped him onto the deck of the launch. The man with the shotgun fired again, then again, then climbed onto the launch behind them. He did not look at Mateo Valverde. He cut the bow line with a knife instead of untying the bad knot.", "The launch pushed off the pilings.", "The black water took them.", "On the dock, the small animals stopped at the edge and watched the launch go. Then they turned and went back into the ferns the way small animals did when a meal was no longer reachable.", "Behind them, beyond the fuel shed, in the deep dark of the trees, something larger took two slow steps.", "It did not come out.", "It listened to the launch leave.", "The man with the shotgun put the gun on the deck.", "He looked at Mateo Valverde for a long second.", "\"Valverde,\" the man said.", "\"Yes.\"", "\"Tomás Araya was a friend of mine.\"", "\"He was a friend of mine too.\"", "The man nodded. He did not say anything else. He turned to the wheel and pushed the throttle. The launch's engine took the water and made a clean sound against it.", "Mateo Valverde sat down on the deck.", "His sleeve was torn.", "His arm under the sleeve was unmarked.", "He looked at the three badges hanging from the lanyard.", "He took Jophery Brown's badge off the lanyard first.", "He held it in his hand for a moment.", "He did not throw it overboard.", "He put it in the breast pocket of his coverall, beside the folded map and the Polaroid of Tomás Araya pretending the cart was a race car.", "He kept Tomás Araya's badge on the lanyard.", "He kept his own.", "The launch moved into the dark, away from the island, toward a horizon that had not yet decided whether it was going to be a dawn."]},
  29: {"n": 29, "title": "Chapter 29: Using the Park", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "North Dock maintenance yard at night, fuel shed, white launch, service gate, bait freezer, hose reel, and yellow bulbs in heavy rain."}, "{{Mateo Valverde}} stopped being polite to the park.", "That was the difference.", "Before North Dock, he had asked doors to open. He had asked radios to believe him. He had asked maps to be right and badges to mean what the plastic said. At North Dock, with a shotgun pointed at his chest and the jungle making {{raptor}} sounds behind the fuel shed, he stopped asking.", "He used what was there.", "The man with the shotgun was named Pike. He worked maintenance launch. He had a name patch on the chest of his rain jacket above a small embroidered fish that meant he had been the kind of man, in a different life, who had liked fishing. He had been told to wait for Brown. He had not been told Brown was dead because InGen information moved like a drain full of hair: slowly, badly, and only after pressure built enough to flood the floor.", "He had been on this dock for two hours.", "He had killed two of the small ones already.", "He had stopped counting after two because counting was the kind of thing a man stopped doing when the things he was counting had begun to come faster than he could give them numbers.", "\"Put the gun down,\" Rosa said.", "Pike did not.", "Mateo Valverde looked past him.", "Fuel shed. Hose reel. Bait freezer for dock scavenger control. Laundry cart with canvas sides. Gate reader. Manual winch. Emergency horn. All things workers used when nobody important watched. All things a man with a folded route sheet and a sanitation contractor's eye could see in their actual order, not in the order the brochure had given them.", "The raptor bark came again.", "Pike turned his head.", "Mateo Valverde moved.", "He did not hit Pike. He hit the emergency horn.", "The dock screamed.", "Every animal in the trees turned toward the sound. Pike fired into leaves. Rosa shoved Luis behind the bait freezer and put her own weight against the shotgun barrel, pushing it down toward the concrete with both hands. Mateo Valverde grabbed the fuel hose, opened the valve, and sprayed diesel across the concrete between the gate and the shed. The diesel came out brown and smelled the way diesel smelled when the diesel had been in a tank too long. He pulled the hose in a wide arc. He pulled it the way he had pulled hoses in the raptor washdown bay, with the kind of grip a man learned when a man had been trained to wash a thing fast and to wash a thing right.", "\"Are you insane?\" Pike shouted.", "\"No.\"", "That was not fully true.", "Mateo Valverde threw one of the road flares.", "The diesel did not explode. Movies lied. It burned ugly and low, a dirty orange line that made heat shimmer over the wet concrete and put a smell in the air so strong even the rain could not flatten it. The line of fire was not a wall. It was a fence. A fence was enough if the thing on the other side was a thing that respected fences, and these animals did not respect fences, but they had learned, in the past two hours of Pike shooting at them, that things which made men move were things they should look at twice before crossing.", "The raptor came to the edge of the light and stopped.", "Not afraid.", "Calculating.", "The eye that watched the fire was not the eye of a thing that had been built to be afraid of fire. The eye was the eye of a thing that had been told once that fire was dangerous and was now testing the proposition.", "Pike looked at Mateo Valverde. Mateo Valverde was already moving. Pike's mouth opened, then closed. Something settled in his face the way a wrench settles into the right size nut. He did not say yes. He let the shotgun barrel come up off the concrete on his own and followed.", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "A dirty orange diesel fire line burning across wet North Dock concrete between a raptor silhouette at the tree edge and the white maintenance launch."}, "Mateo Valverde used {{Tomás Araya}}'s badge on the bait freezer.", "Green.", "He opened it and almost vomited from the smell. Old meat. Fish heads. Something labeled GOAT PARTS - DO NOT USE GUEST CART. The bin was the bin a worker put a thing in when the thing was no longer fit to feed a guest's animal but might be fit to feed a working animal, and the working animals on this dock had been the dogs the security men had used, before the security men had stopped having dogs.", "He shoved the bait bin onto the laundry cart.", "\"Push,\" he told Pike.", "\"What?\"", "\"Push the cart.\"", "\"To where?\"", "Mateo Valverde pointed at the gate reader.", "Pike looked at the fire. Then at the raptor. Then at Mateo Valverde, who was temporary and no longer asking.", "They pushed.", "The bad wheel on the laundry cart screamed. The raptor's head followed the sound. Mateo Valverde slapped {{Jophery Brown}}'s badge against the gate reader.", "Red.", "INVALID - DECEASED EMPLOYEE.", "Luis came out from behind the freezer, dragging one boot, and called over the horn. \"Service gate. Tomás's card. The east post, not this one.\" He pointed his hand flat at the post, the way a kitchen man pointed across a counter to the right tray. He sat back down. He had used his last useful breath on that pointing, and the pointing had been correct, the way a kitchen man's pointing was always correct because a kitchen man had been fired once for pointing wrong.", "Mateo Valverde moved his hand to the east reader and used Tomás Araya's badge.", "Green.", "The gate opened.", "Mateo Valverde kicked the bait cart through. It rolled down the slight service slope, bad wheel screaming, meat smell pouring out behind it. The raptor crossed the fire line in one jump and went after the cart. The animal cleared the fire because the animal had decided the cart was worth the discomfort of warm feet for two seconds. The animal had calculated the cost.", "The second raptor did not.", "It had come from the dock side.", "It stood between them and the launch.", "Mateo Valverde looked at his own cracked temporary badge.", "One local exit, the system had said.", "He pressed it to the launch access reader.", "The reader did not go red the polite way.", "The screen woke up. White text on black. Three words.", "TEMP CREDENTIAL EXPIRED.", "The park said his name one last time and said it with contempt.", "Mateo Valverde took the box cutter out of his pocket and began the seal."]},
  30: {"n": 30, "title": "Chapter 30: Left Behind", "paragraphs": [{"type": "image", "src": "scene-1.webp", "alt": "Dawn at North Dock after the storm, a maintenance launch pulling from the pier, smoke rising over wet concrete, three badges scattered on the deck."}, "The launch access reader did not care that {{Mateo Valverde}} was alive.", "The screen still showed it.", "TEMP CREDENTIAL EXPIRED.", "He tried {{Tomás Araya}}'s badge.", "Red.", "{{Jophery Brown}}'s.", "Red.", "Three cards. Three little deaths.", "Pike shouted something from the dock. Rosa shouted back. Luis was coughing behind the fuel shed. The second {{raptor}} stood between the people and the boat with its head low and its tail held still. The fire made orange lines along its wet back.", "Mateo Valverde looked at the reader.", "Not the light.", "The screws.", "Four screws. Two rusted. One missing. One replaced with the wrong size.", "He laughed then, one short ugly sound, because of course.", "The park had not been built by miracles. It had been built by people who lost screws and covered the hole with tape. It had been maintained by men like Jophery Brown and Tomás Araya, who wrote warnings no one read. It could be opened the same way.", "He used the box cutter on the reader seal and the wrench on the wrong screw. The panel came loose enough to show wires. Red, black, yellow, green. He had seen the same colors in the hospital laundry lift. He had seen them in the bar's beer cooler. He had seen them in the back of every machine that men had built and other men had been hired to fix, and the colors had always meant the same things, because the men who built machines and the men who fixed them were the same men in different rooms. He touched red to green.", "The launch gate opened.", "Pike fired once. The raptor snapped sideways, not hit, only annoyed. Rosa threw the mop handle. It struck the fuel shed wall. The animal turned toward that smaller insult.", "\"Now,\" Mateo Valverde said.", "He did not shout it. He had no air to shout. He said it the way men said things in a kitchen when smoke meant you needed to leave the line.", "Everyone moved.", "Luis fell into the boat more than climbed. Rosa followed. Pike jumped down and started the engine with shaking hands. Mateo Valverde stayed at the reader with the wires pinched together until the gate finished its slow travel.", "The raptor saw him.", "For one second Mateo Valverde saw himself in its eye: wet, small, temporary, holding two wires because the official way had failed.", "Then the launch engine caught.", "Rosa reached for him.", "Mateo Valverde let go of the wires and ran.", "He made three steps before the raptor crossed the dock.", "Not enough steps.", "Rosa screamed his name. That was the important part. Not the pain in his shoulder, not the wood under his back, not Pike pulling the launch away because Rosa would have jumped back onto the dock if the boat stayed close enough to let her.", "His name.", "Mateo.", "The boat moved into gray water.", "The raptor dragged him once, then let go when the emergency horn cut through the dock again.", "Not the dock horn.", "Something larger.", "Aircraft.", "Mateo Valverde rolled onto his side. The dock boards were hot under his cheek from the diesel fire. Above the black line of jungle, three helicopters came in low over the island. Behind them, farther out, fixed-wing aircraft held a steady line over the water. The fixed-wing aircraft had bays. The bays were open.", "Rex weather was something you could run from. There was no name for what was coming next.", "For one clean second, Mateo Valverde thought rescue had finally learned his route.", "He pushed himself up with one hand. The other arm did not answer. He lifted Jophery Brown's badge instead. It had fallen near his knee, cloudy plastic catching dawn light.", "\"Here,\" he said, though no one could hear. \"Here.\"", {"type": "image", "src": "scene-2.webp", "alt": "Mateo on the burning dock lifting Jophery's badge toward approaching aircraft, mistaking the firebombing run for rescue."}, "The first canister fell beyond the visitor center.", "It did not look like a bomb from far away. It looked like cargo. A gray shape released from a machine and turning slowly, almost gently, as it dropped through the wet air.", "Then the trees became fire.", "Not fire like the diesel line. Not orange along the ground. This fire opened upward. It filled the jungle in one breath, a sheet of white and yellow that turned rain into steam before the rain touched it.", "The second canister fell closer.", "Mateo Valverde understood then.", "Not all at once. His mind tried to keep the rescue shape for another second. Helicopters meant people coming down. Aircraft meant help. Uniforms meant someone with a board, asking names. A country did not burn its own island while a worker still held up a badge.", "Except the board said he had left.", "Except the system had corrected the mismatch.", "Except Mateo Valverde was already safely departed on paper.", "The radio on the dock crackled through static.", "\"...all personnel clear...\"", "The voice on the radio was not Pike. The voice on the radio was a voice from the sky. The voice was reading from a list. The list had been printed before dawn by a printer in a room with a manifest under a plastic cover. The list was the list the building had remembered. The list did not have his name on it.", "The third canister struck near the fuel shed.", "The air hit him before the fire did. It knocked him backward against the open launch gate and filled his mouth with hot metal. The plastic sleeve of papers burst open. Manifest, complaint, reconciliation page, Tomás Araya's Polaroid, all of it lifted around him for one bright second like the park had decided to snow paper before it burned.", "Mateo Valverde saw Jophery Brown's complaint catch fire at the corner.", "He saw his own temporary badge melt inward, photograph bending, name warping but not gone yet.", "He pressed the two badges together in his good hand.", "One dead man the system remembered.", "One living man the system had not.", "He looked at Jophery Brown's badge. He looked at the water under the dock. He looked at the aircraft. The turn would have continued past the aircraft, across the line of jungle, back toward the visitor center and the kitchen and the road. His shoulders started the motion. They did not finish it. He was facing the water again before he knew he had stopped.", "The water was the gulf, dark and wide. The water was eight blocks from his mother's apartment, which was an apartment in Puntarenas, on a hill, with a loose pipe under the sink that an inner tube was holding together. The water was the same water that had been under the <i>Anne B. II</i> nine days ago when he had ridden it across with Cliff Donegan and Paola Ruiz and two badged workers who had said <i>Jophery was good</i>. The water did not care what the building's manifest said about him. The water had never been told about him. The water had no list.", "He thought about his mother.", "He thought about Tomás Araya's sister, and that he had not asked her name.", "He thought about Jophery Brown's daughters and the cake on the youngest one's chin.", "He thought about Eduardo Brenes saying <i>a boat is a thing you can leave in</i>.", "The fourth canister fell.", "This time he did not mistake it for rescue."]}
};
